tsd:news_padi_web_171178_afrikanische_schweinepest_kreis_altenkirchen_richtet_sperrzone_ein a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:171178-afrikanische-schweinepest--kreis-altenkirchen-richtet-sperrzone-ein" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "ba86da564c1c5097f46fb09251e6820a1073394a1116a0133efe059411637287" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "African swine fever: Altenkirchen district establishes exclusion zone" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# African swine fever: Altenkirchen district establishes exclusion zone

African swine fever: Altenkirchen district establishes exclusion zone

Press release from 21.05.2026     
African swine fever: Altenkirchen district establishes exclusion zone

African swine fever is getting closer and closer to the district of Altenkirchen.

Although the virus has not yet arrived in the region, the authorities have now taken preventive measures.

A new exclusion zone is intended to prevent the spread of the disease.

Symbolic image (Photo: Pixabay)

Altenkirchen district.

African swine fever (ASF) has still not arrived in the district of Altenkirchen, but it is getting closer and closer - more precisely: to twelve kilometers.

Positive cases in the area of Kreuztal and Netphen in the Siegen-Wittgenstein district have now also prompted those responsible in Rhineland-Palatinate to take further measures: A few days ago, the district of Altenkirchen and the Ministry of Agriculture, Viticulture, Environment and Forestry proposed to the EU Commission an extension of the restricted area to Rhineland-Palatinate territory.

This was granted, so that the district can issue a corresponding general decree, which will be available via the district's website from Friday, May 22, 2026 (www.kreis-altenkirchen.de).

The so-called exclusion zone I includes the entire Verbandsgemeinde Kirchen, the local community of Grünebach, the cities of Herdorf and Daaden as well as the local community of Emmerzhausen.

This covers a corridor about 7 kilometers wide to the state border with North Rhine-Westphalia.

At the same time, a fence will be built that stretches from Wildenburger Land to the Stegskopf.

Route inspections have already taken place.

"Despite this measure, which at first glance seems drastic, there is no reason to panic.

The designation of the exclusion zone is purely a precautionary measure," emphasizes District Administrator ----------------.

First and foremost, those entitled to hunt and pig farmers are affected.

For citizens, nothing will change for the time being, there will be no restrictions.

However, ---------- asks that the applicable rules of conduct in the forest be observed.

Rules of conduct
For example, driven and movement hunts will be prohibited in the exclusion zone in the future.

Killed wild boar must be reported to the veterinary office for sampling.

Special collection points for hunted or found animals are also planned.

Pig farmers must also be prepared for increased safety precautions.

In contrast, both public and private events remain possible within the exclusion zone, although increased caution is requested here as well, even if the virus is not transmissible to humans.

The following still applies: Hikers and cyclists should never leave leftovers in the forest or at rest areas.

Waste of this kind should only be disposed of in closed containers, but it is best to take it home with you.

If a dead wild boar is found, the nearest police station or the responsible hunter should be informed immediately.

Fence route
After swine fever had initially concentrated in the districts of Olpe and the Hochsauerland district, the district had erected a first five-kilometre-long protective fence in the area of Wildenburg railway station last year.

At that time, there was little to indicate that the disease was spreading towards AK country.

The new fence routes begin in the north at Hammerhöhe/Hohenhain.

The gate then runs east of Friesenhagen on the state border with North Rhine-Westphalia.

The fence leads through the Giebelwald, past Niederfischbach, crosses the B62 at Mudersbach and follows the Dermbach to Herdorf.

From Herdorf, the route is oriented towards the state border and runs via the Malscheid to the state road between Emmerzhausen and Lippe.

This is followed by another ASP protective fence in the Westerwaldkreis.

"We hope that we can prevent ASF from spreading to the north of Rhineland-Palatinate.

But once again my appeal: Fences alone will not protect us, each individual is called upon to exercise special caution in the forest," explains District Administrator Enders in conclusion.

(PM)

More on this:   

Environment & Health  

Feedback: Notes to editors

AK-Kurier Newsletter: Always well informed

Every day at 8 p.m., the latest news, events and job offers in the region are conveniently delivered to your inbox free of charge.""" ;
