tsd:news_padi_web_171954_jasno_v_kauze_uhynulych_holubu_v_moste_slo_o_jed_na_krysy a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:171954-jasno-v-kauze-uhynulych-holubu-v-moste-slo-o-jed-na-krysy" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "5fe47a83a83a9254c09d7116a29f5dfb22416f19451105ac15e08ced60e31ad5" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Clarity on the case of dead pigeons in Most. It was rat poison" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Clarity on the case of dead pigeons in Most. It was rat poison

Clarity on the case of dead pigeons in Most.

It was rat poison

Most – The two-month-long uncertainty and fears of the inhabitants of Most are over.

The mass death of hundreds of wild wood pigeons, which took place in the streets and housing estates in March, finally has a clear explanation.

The results of specialized toxicological analyses confirmed that the human factor is behind the destruction of birds.

"We finally got the results from the laboratory.

It has been confirmed that someone poisoned them with rat poison," said the commander of the Most Municipal Police, --------------.

The case, which has been filling the pages of regional media since mid-March and causing serious concern among the public, began like a bolt from the blue.

In just two weeks, Most police officers began to collect dozens of dead birds on the streets and in housing estates every day.

The number of finds escalated to alarming hundreds of pieces at that time.

On a single Friday in March, patrols cleared over twenty of them, while the phones at the technical services were constantly rattling due to further suggestions from citizens.

From bird flu to a toxicological trail
The initial fears were focused on the risk of dangerous infection.

Bird flu or the dreaded paramyxovirus, known as the "pigeon plague", was at play.

The Regional Veterinary Administration together with the Regional Hygiene Station in Ústí nad Labem therefore urgently carried out a series of tests.

However, these most common infectious diseases have been completely eliminated as negative.

When the city of Most paid for a second, extended series of tests for less common bird diseases from its own budget, and they also proved nothing, the range of options narrowed.

The investigators had to resort to the most terrifying option – deliberately hitting the population with a toxic substance.

The city had to allocate additional funds for the final toxicological analyses, which eventually brought the desired resolution.

The mystery of selective death
The case was accompanied by one big unknown, which puzzled the experts for a long time: how is it possible that a toxic substance has so selectively affected only the wild population of pigeons, specifically the wood pigeon species?

Fortunately, other species of birds, and most importantly, even free-roaming pets, did not show any symptoms of poisoning.

Registered breeders also remained in absolute calm all the time.

According to ---------------- from the local association of the Czech-Moravian Association of Carrier Pigeon Breeders, there were no losses in private breeding.

Organized breeders are obliged to strictly vaccinate their birds, which acts as a reliable shield against diseases.

This also indirectly pointed to the fact that the cause of death of wild birds lies outside the common biological pathogen and is related to a locally planted substance in the field.

Due to the official confirmation of the presence of rodenticides (rat poison) in the bodies of dead animals, the whole matter is passing into the hands of the Police of the Czech Republic.

In accordance with their earlier statements, the Municipal Police will file a criminal complaint against an unknown perpetrator on suspicion of animal cruelty and unauthorized handling of dangerous substances.

The search will be a long run
Although the cause of death is now finally clear, it will be extremely complicated to find out the specific culprit who placed the dangerous poison on the streets of Most.

The commander of the municipal police, --------------, himself expressed a certain degree of scepticism about the real chances of catching the perpetrator.

The municipality and the municipal police thank the residents of Most for their cooperation in the March monitoring and reporting of dead animals.

It was thanks to the lightning-fast reaction of the public, police officers and employees of the Technical Services of the City of Most that the affected localities were effectively cleaned and thus minimized the risk that other animal species or, for example, small children in housing estates could encounter.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
