    ts:sourceContentHash "af0a99bc66b8e3d6931369233c83aa6c8a4c785628a00627705b8ea26c4b3922" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Close Follow-up of Bird Flu and Pseudo-Plague in Amasya" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Close Follow-up of Bird Flu and Pseudo-Plague in Amasya

Close Follow-up of Bird Flu and Pseudo-Plague in Amasya

The "Poultry Survey Studies", which are carried out regularly every year by the Amasya Provincial Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry, were successfully completed this year as well.

Within the scope of the work carried out by the Animal Health, Breeding and Aquaculture Branch teams, examinations were made in commercial poultry houses and village poultry areas.

In the field studies carried out under the coordination of the Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, various samples were taken for the early diagnosis of infectious diseases that can be seen in poultry.

It was stated that screening studies for Newcastle Disease (ND - False Chicken Plague) and Avian Influenza (AI - Bird Flu) diseases were carried out meticulously.

During the visits made by the teams, producers were informed about biosecurity measures, disease symptoms and protective practices.

It was stated that controls are continuing in areas where village poultry farming is carried out as well as commercial enterprises.

Amasya Provincial Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry officials stated that the main purpose of the studies carried out is to detect infectious disease agents at an early stage and prevent their spread.

It was also emphasized that it is aimed to protect disease-free zones and to maintain reliable food supply in a sustainable manner.

Pointing out that the protection of animal health is of great importance for both producers and public health, the authorities stated that regular survey studies will continue in the future.

Thanks to the field studies carried out, it is aimed to keep possible disease risks in poultry farming under control and to support healthy production.

It was also stated that inspection and follow-up activities will continue uninterruptedly for the continuity of reliable food supply.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
