    ts:sourceURL "https://turkmenportal.com/tr/news/84717-kanadada-gush-dumewi-bilen-kesellan-ilkinji-hassa-hasaba-alyndy-------------------"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_92442 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:92442" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "fe767baab1f9ce3d1c717a054c5dcb45fb834f57b546c53b7a754e72a2a2c88e" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu

Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu

The USDA Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service confirmed another commercial poultry flock in Minnesota has tested positive for highly pathogenic avian influenza this month, bringing the tally to four commercial flocks so far in May.

APHIS said the most recent detection was confirmed in Becker County on May 20 and affected a commercial breeder operation.

Four flocks in May
Becker County has been the site of all four of the state's May detections, and the county lost a reported 66,400 head of commercial poultry to HPAI during the month.

Two of the other infected operations in Becker County were also described as commercial breeder operations, while the fourth was listed as commercial turkey breeder replacement hens.

66,400 birds lost
Before this cluster in Becker County, the most recent Minnesota confirmation was reported in mid-April in a commercial meat turkey flock in Big Stone County.

Outside Minnesota, the only other state with a confirmed commercial poultry case so far in May is Indiana, according to APHIS reporting.

Becker County cluster
APHIS described the May 20 affected site as a commercial breeder operation that housed 4,300 birds.

Calls to depopulate or quarantine affected flocks and to apply biosecurity measures are standard following confirmations, and APHIS is the reporting agency for those actions.

4,300 birds in flock
State and federal officials continue to track detections and publish case information as investigations proceed.

APHIS maintains case listings and updates as investigations confirm cases and determine the scope of affected operations.

Tracking cases
Producers and industry stakeholders looking for an interactive view of recent commercial-poultry HPAI detections across North America can consult the map available at WATTPoultry.com, which tracks confirmed cases in the United States, Mexico and Canada.

The APHIS case reports and the WATTPoultry map currently show Minnesota’s May cluster concentrated in Becker County and a separate commercial confirmation in Indiana.

Photo - img.wattagnet.com""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:43.959140+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://agronews.com/us/en/news/agrosphere/2026-05-23/92442"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_93_a_sessao_geral_da_assembleia_mundial_de_delegados_da_woah a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:93-a-sessao-geral-da-assembleia-mundial-de-delegados-da-woah" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "c3a8783627b58843a5e65c17bd29f6259a0a4373aeb01ad11960fe22e3ba11ea" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "93rd General Session of the WOAH World Assembly of Delegates" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# 93rd General Session of the WOAH World Assembly of Delegates

93rd General Session of the WOAH World Assembly of Delegates
The 93rd General Session of the World Assembly of Delegates of the World Organization for Animal Health (WOAH) took place in Paris from 18 to 22 May, bringing together 183 WOAH members and representatives of international organizations from various regions, cultures and disciplines, to discuss some of the most important challenges facing the future of our world today.

On May 18, the 2026 Animal Health Merit Awards ceremony took place, in which the President of the Organization, Dr. Susana Pombo, and the Director-General, Dr. Emmanuelle Soubeyran, together with the World Assembly of Delegates of the WOAH, officially recognized the achievements of the
winners
.

On May 19, the
PREVENT Forum
, a new platform designed to strengthen the prevention of animal diseases, mainly through improved vaccination strategies.

The animal health forum addressed the importance of investing in animal health and in the words of
Emmanuelle Soubeyran
Director General of WOAH
, investing in animal health is not
optional, is essential and should be considered as a strategic investment.

A declaration was also signed by a large number of Ministers from WOAH countries in favour of a global push to invest in animal health, stressing the importance of remembering that animal health is fundamental to food security, livelihoods, trade, biodiversity and global health security.

During the forum, the
revision of the OIE standard
on trade and the drafting of a new resolution on biosafety.

On May 20, after months of consultations, the
8th WOAH Strategic Plan
, marking a pivotal moment for global animal health as WOAH members agree on a common roadmap for the period 2027-2031.

This year also marks the
30th anniversary
of the WOAH's official recognition system of animal health status.

Over the past three decades, this mechanism has been a key pillar of transparency, trust and science-based international trade, while recognising the continued efforts of WOAH members and veterinary services around the world.

During an intense and inspiring week, in addition to the adopted resolutions and technical discussions, the essential role of veterinary services was reaffirmed and the strength and relevance of the WOAH was demonstrated.

This week conveys a strong collective message, of multilateral collaboration at various levels, based on trust, science and solidarity that, in the face of the complex challenges facing the world, remains not only relevant, but indispensable, and represents a powerful contribution to global stability and sustainable development, says Susana Pombo, President of the WOAH Council and Director-General of DGAV at the closing of the 93rd General Session.

The 94th General Session of the WOAH World Assembly of Delegates will take place in Paris from 24 to 28 May 2027.

See all the information on
WOAH website
See the
Photos
May 22, 2026""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:57.851731+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.dgav.pt/destaques/noticias/93-a-sessao-geral-da-assembleia-mundial-de-delegados-da-woah/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_afrikanische_schweinepest_asp_breitet_sich_weiter_aus_664648_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:Afrikanische-Schweinepest-ASP-breitet-sich-weiter-aus-664648.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "c1722b4e6aad494be0d1d9d3badd6e05ac01b07981443f55641ca3845dfa82d9" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "African swine fever (ASF) continues to spread" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# African swine fever (ASF) continues to spread

African swine fever (ASF) continues to spread

Westerwald district.

In June 2025, the district of Olpe recorded the first case of African swine fever (ASF) in wild boars in North Rhine-Westphalia.

Since then, the animal disease has continued to spread there and 637 cases have already been detected (as of 11.05.2026).

The district of Siegen-Wittgenstein, which borders the Westerwaldkreis, is also affected, and the nearest case occurred only about 22 kilometers from the border of the Westerwaldkreis.

In order to prevent ASF from spreading to the Westerwaldkreis, the Rhineland-Palatinate Ministry for Climate Protection, Environment, Energy and Mobility (MKUEM) intends to erect a protective fence together with the Westerwaldkreis in the near future.

This is to run along the state border in the local communities of Stein-Neukirch and Liebenscheid from the Stegskopf camp to the border triangle.

The preparations for this are in full swing, the costs are covered by the MKUEM.

Care will be taken to keep the restrictions for citizens as low as possible: Planned culverts will continue to allow the use of hiking and cycling trails.

Practical solutions are also being created for the crossings of the L 296 and the B 54.

The protective fence is to be continued in the district of Altenkirchen along the state border.

"We are aware that fence construction entails restrictions.

At the same time, this measure is essential to protect domestic pigs and wild boars in our region from African swine fever," explains the veterinary office of the Westerwaldkreis and asks the population for their understanding.

ASF is harmless to humans and other animal species, but infection is usually fatal for pigs.

A vaccine is not yet available.

ASF is a notifiable animal disease with the highest control priority.

The virus is transmitted to the pigs through direct contact with infected pigs, through the ingestion of pathogen-containing (raw) pork/products or through indirect transmission, for example through contact with contaminated equipment, feed or bedding.

In order to detect a possible occurrence of ASF in wild boars at an early stage, all wild boars shot in the municipalities of Bad Marienberg, Hachenburg, Rennerod and Westerburg must be tested for the animal disease since March 2026.

In addition, all wild boars found dead or shot sick or with behavioural problems must be examined for ASF at the Koblenz State Investigation Office (LUA).

As part of this intensive monitoring, 227 wild boars have been examined so far - all results were negative.

If citizens discover a dead wild boar, they should inform the veterinary administration under veterinaeramt@westerwaldkreis.de.

The immediate vicinity of the place where it was found should be avoided and the animal carcass should not be touched.

Further information on ASF can be found at www.westerwaldkreis.de.

Press release Westerwald district""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:55:12.389910+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.blick-aktuell.de/Nachrichten/Afrikanische-Schweinepest-ASP-breitet-sich-weiter-aus-664648.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_afrikanische_schweinepest_weiterhin_vorsicht_geboten_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:afrikanische+schweinepest_+weiterhin+vorsicht+geboten.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "77b146e03b1e473626b75a1b9174f773c6d170d3b875b526a51029839a2ad37a" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "African swine fever: Caution still required" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# African swine fever: Caution still required

African swine fever: Caution still required

The consistent measures taken to contain African swine fever (ASF) have had an effect in recent months: In the Rhein-Neckar district, the last confirmed positive ASF case was more than nine months ago.

To ensure that the situation remains stable - especially against the background of the flare-up of the epidemic in the neighboring Bergstraße district - the Rhein-Neckar-Kreis District Office is once again appealing to continue to comply with the applicable rules.

Unfortunately, it has recently been observed again and again that the leash requirement for dogs in particular is disregarded.

The responsible veterinary office in the Rhein-Neckar-Kreis district office therefore urges all citizens and visitors to continue to strictly observe the applicable rules of conduct in exclusion zone II.

Observe rules of conduct in exclusion zone II

Leash requirement: In exclusion zone II, dogs must be kept on a leash in the forest and vineyards in order not to scare up the game populations.

Leisure activities in the forest:

Cycling, horseback riding and walking are only allowed on paved or marked paths.

Barbecuing in the forest:

Barbecue areas in the forest may not be used.

Barbecue areas that are located within or in the immediate vicinity (max. 100 meters) of built-up areas are excluded.

Close ASP protective fences: Gates in the protective fences must be closed again after passing through.

Damage to the fence must be reported immediately to the veterinary office (veterinaeramt@rhein-neckar-kreis.de).

Report finds: Anyone who discovers a dead wild boar or a dead young boar should inform the responsible veterinary office (veterinaeramt@rhein-neckar-kreis.de) immediately.

Laudenbach, Hemsbach, Weinheim, Heddesheim, Hirschberg, Ilvesheim, Ladenburg, Schriesheim, Wilhelmsfeld, Heiligkreuzsteinach, Dossenheim, Edingen-Neckarhausen are currently in exclusion zone II.

Violations will be punished
Demonstrable violations of the applicable rules will be punished consistently.

Depending on the type of violation, fines of up to 30,000 euros can be imposed under the Animal Health Act.

Cases of vandalism or the theft of fence elements are particularly serious – here there is not only the threat of severe fines, but also criminal consequences.

Further information:
www.rhein-neckar-kreis.de/asp""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-26"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:50:20.045019+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.rhein-neckar-kreis.de/start/aktuelles/afrikanische+schweinepest_+weiterhin+vorsicht+geboten.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_alberta_avian_flu_outbreaks_bird_9_7207997 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:alberta-avian-flu-outbreaks-bird-9.7207997" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "f3e17a259452d8a56abc40f398d0b507d98778791bca3e6891415701468d36bf" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Here's how Alberta zoos are protecting birds from avian flu" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Here's how Alberta zoos are protecting birds from avian flu

Here's how Alberta zoos are protecting birds from avian flu

Listen to this articleEstimated 5 minutesThe audio version of this article is generated by AI-based technology.

Mispronunciations can occur.

We are working with our partners to continually review and improve the results.

The presence of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) in Alberta birds means zoos need to take precautions to protect their birds from the virus.

The Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) says there have been three outbreaks of avian flu at commercial poultry operations in Alberta as of May 24."So far, HPAI detections during 2026 spring migration have been relatively comparable with previous years," the CFIA said in a statement.

"However, the continued detections of HPAI in both wild and domestic birds in Canada is a strong reminder for anyone raising birds to remain vigilant of HPAI and ensure they have effective biosecurity measures in place.

"Outbreaks in Alberta have been detected east of Edmonton and near Ribstone Creek in east-central Alberta on May 11, and northeast of Drumheller on May 16.Calgary Zoo closes popular aviaryThe detection of avian flu within 200 kilometres of the Wilder Institute/Calgary Zoo is cause for concern, the organization said Friday in a social media post.

The zoo is "proactively implementing" certain measures to keep its birds safe from the virus, including having guests use foot baths at the entrances of the Penguin Plunge and Rainforest Aviary.

The zoo has closed walk-in access to the Jihad Shibley Rocky Mountain Aviary, which houses free-flying owls, until further notice.

"The health and well-being of the animals in our care remains our top priority," the zoo said.

The Edmonton Valley Zoo says it is keeping tabs on the situation east of Edmonton, where an avian flu outbreak was reported on May 11."We are aware of the infected commercial flock in Strathcona County and are monitoring the situation," the zoo said in a statement.

"During times of increased risk, we take several precautions to protect the zoo’s bird population.

Our birds are either transferred indoors, moved from public display, or moved to habitats with outdoor space protected by mesh to keep out wild birds that could spread the virus.

"WATCH | Bird flu cases found around Edmonton last fall:New bird flu cases found around EdmontonOfficials have confirmed cases of avian influenza at a commercial poultry facility in Strathcona County, and another facility in Leduc is under investigation.

It's the latest set of bird flu cases in the province since a recent outbreak at a petting zoo in Calgary.

----------- is a biological sciences professor at the University of Alberta who researches avian influenza.

The Alberta Birds of Prey Foundation wildlife rehabilitation centre in Coaldale, where injured wild birds brought in for treatment may end up in close proximity to captive birds on public display, doesn't take any chances when it comes to avian flu.

"We will not accept any birds with symptoms of avian flu into our facilities," said managing director ----------.

"That's just in case it puts the other birds we have in captivity at risk," he said of the deadly virus.

"There's nothing that can be done for those creatures.

"Alberta Birds of Prey Foundation managing director ---------- holds one of the facility's captive snowy owls.

The site covers 70 acres of wetland in Coaldale, east of Lethbridge, and is home to a wide variety of birds housed there for rehabilitation or, if release into the wild is not a possibility, as permanent residents.

(---------/CBC)Weir said the centre gets "a lot of calls about avian flu" in wild birds from October to March, when waterfowl are migrating.

"It's more likely to spread amongst those populations at times when they're getting together in groups and flocks," he said.

"And then it's amplified even more in the wintertime, when there are small open pools of water in frozen lakes" where many birds bathe, drink and defecate in the same spots, he said.12 cases of avian flu in Alberta wildlife this year: federal databaseA federal database tracking avian flu detections in wildlife across Canada lists 12 cases in Alberta birds found in 2026 as of May 24, the majority of which are Canada geese.

There have been 76 avian flu detections in wildlife across Canada this year, more than two-thirds of which have been in Ontario.

With last year's avian flu season considered the worst in years, the Alberta government says it is closely monitoring the avian flu situation.

"When cases are detected in Alberta, the CFIA leads the disease response, and we work with them and industry to inform producers and support the response," Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation spokesperson ----------- said in a statement.

He said details will not be shared publicly about the three commercial poultry operations in Alberta where avian flu outbreaks have been detected.

WATCH | Infectious disease experts keep close eye on avian flu cases in Calgary:Infectious disease experts keep close eye on avian flu cases in CalgaryAt least 12 people are being tested for H5N1 avian influenza in the city.

The disease was discovered over the weekend at a petting zoo near the northwest community of Rocky Ridge.

Experts say the risk to the public is low, but the situation is still being monitoring closely.

The CFIA says there have been 19 avian flu outbreaks confirmed in domestic bird flocks across Canada so far this year, seven of which have been in Alberta's neighbouring province of Saskatchewan.

The Alberta government says people should avoid handling live or dead wild birds, and that anyone who comes across dead waterfowl or raptors should call 310-0000 to report it.

Some birds like songbirds and woodpeckers are not likely to be affected by avian flu, while some mammals like skunks, seals and cattle are.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-24"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:51:48.887622+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-avian-flu-outbreaks-bird-9.7207997"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_alteracoes_aos_requisitos_de_exportacao_para_a_china_entrada_em_vigor_do_decreto_n_o_280_da_gacc a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:alteracoes-aos-requisitos-de-exportacao-para-a-china-entrada-em-vigor-do-decreto-n-o-280-da-gacc" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "49bb17f9e691d220b1a5687915969f714e720b2b216afc498cb88261673b6eda" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Changes to Export Requirements to China | Entry into force of Decree No. 280 of the GACC." ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Changes to Export Requirements to China | Entry into force of Decree No. 280 of the GACC.

Changes to Export Requirements to China | Entry into force of Decree No. 280 of the GACC.

The DGAV informs all economic operators that, with effect from
June 1, 2026
, the General Administration of Customs of the People's Republic of China (
GACC
) will revoke Decree No. 248, introducing in its place the
Decree No. 280
, regulated by the
Implementation Announcement No. 27/2026
, published on 18 March 2026.

In this way, we share
Decree 280
, such as
Interpretation of the decree
made by the Chinese authorities.

Decree 280 is based on decree 248 regarding the system of registration, control and supervision of foreign establishments that produce, process or store food destined for the Chinese market through the platform
CIFER
, with some amendments.

According to the available information, the existing records on the CIFER platform remain valid.

Notwithstanding some adjustments that may occur in the implementation phase,
The main Changes to the Registration Procedure are explained:
Changes to the Product Catalog:
The most significant change translates into the exclusion of certain primary agricultural products that were previously on the list of Decree No. 248.

Thus,
are no longer subject to the recommendation procedure via CIFER

The following products:
Fresh vegetables and dried beans;
Oilseeds;
Unroasted coffee and cocoa beans.

Operators wishing to export these specific AGs should take into account that these products are transferred to different phytosanitary control and quarantine regimes, in the procedures of the
GACC Announcement No. 219/2025
Updated List of the 17 Categories considered to be at risk and subject to CA Recommendation (DGAV):
Meat and meat products
Casings
Bird nests and derivatives
Bee products
Eggs and egg products
Dairy products
Aquatic products (fish and fishery products other than live aquatic animals)
Edible Oils and Fats
Stuffed wheat products
Edible cereals
Products of the grain and malt milling industry
Dehydrated vegetables
Condiments Powder
Nuts and seeds
Nuts
Foods for dietary purposes
Healthy foods
It is advised that in the case of animal RA, the registration of temperature-controlled warehouses is necessary, with the exception of dairy product warehouses.

Simplification of Submission:

For products that require a recommendation from the DGAV (the highest risk categories listed above), operators will now be able to submit their requests
directly on the CIFER platform
.

It will be the responsibility of the Operator to attach the letter of recommendation and the respective Control Checklist, issued by this Authority, eliminating the need for centralized submission by the DGAV on the CIFER platform.

In addition to this modality, there is still the previous registration mechanism, in which companies submit the application through the CIFER platform to the DGAV, which reviews the process and, if in compliance, attaches the necessary documentation and submits it to GACC.
List Registration (
List-Based
):
An expedited batch registration mechanism for countries with specific bilateral agreements is introduced, allowing for the validation of lists of companies audited by national authorities.

Automatic Renewal and Extension of the renewal period:

In the light of Decree 280, eligible sectors will benefit from a
Automatic renewal of registrations valid for 5 years
, thus alleviating the administrative burden.

Meat and meat products establishments are excluded from this automatic renewal, having a longer time window to submit the renewal request, from 3 to 6 months for
3 to 12 months before the expiry date
.

The information provided here does not exempt the information from the official channels of the authority of the PR China
.

May 26, 2026""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-26"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:50:31.504256+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.dgav.pt/destaques/noticias/alteracoes-aos-requisitos-de-exportacao-para-a-china-entrada-em-vigor-do-decreto-n-o-280-da-gacc/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_amasyada_kanatli_hayvanlara_kus_gribi_taramasi a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:amasyada-kanatli-hayvanlara-kus-gribi-taramasi" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "78c24630f3bd41735f9f029659aedd2d95447d8ce9c125829581dd65928b923b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Bird Flu Screening for Poultry in Amasya" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Bird Flu Screening for Poultry in Amasya

Bird Flu Screening for Poultry in Amasya

Amasya Provincial Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry carried out a comprehensive bird flu and newcastle control for poultry in Göynücek district.

Under the coordination of the Amasya Provincial Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry, an active survey study for poultry health was carried out by the ------------- of the Göynücek District Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry.

Within the scope of the studies carried out, field investigations and controls were carried out against Avian Influenza (Bird Flu) and Newcastle diseases that can be seen in poultry.

Necessary follow-up studies were carried out by ------------- for early diagnosis of diseases, prevention of their spread and protection of animal health.

Officials pointed out that regular screening and survey studies are of great importance in the fight against animal diseases and stated that producers should also comply with biosecurity rules sensitively.

Amasya Provincial Directorate of Agriculture and Forestry stated that field studies will continue uninterruptedly in order to protect animal health and prevent possible epidemics.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-25"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
