tsd:news_padi_web_amenzi_pentru_unii_romani_care_stau_la_tara_se_verifica_gospodariile_cu_animale_cine_va_achita_1_200_de_lei_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:amenzi-pentru-unii-romani-care-stau-la-tara-se-verifica-gospodariile-cu-animale-cine-va-achita-1-200-de-lei.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "92b4b14d43cb15bade9b45036f4fd1590cc55e6a1a8adac32ee6960c5e9d6660" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Fines for some Romanians who live in the countryside. Households with animals are checked. Who will pay 1,200 lei" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Fines for some Romanians who live in the countryside. Households with animals are checked. Who will pay 1,200 lei

Fines for some Romanians who live in the countryside.

Households with animals are checked.

Who will pay 1,200 lei

From the content of the article
The official veterinarians of DSVSA Satu Mare – the Official Control Service for Animal Health and Welfare – carried out, in a single week, a number of 79 controls in professional and non-professional farms, markets, veterinary sanitary offices and veterinary pharmacies.

Following the checks, the inspectors applied five contravention sanctions, of which three fines totaling 3,600 lei and two warnings.

According to the institution, the sanctions were applied for the sale or alienation of animals without the documents provided by the sanitary-veterinary legislation in force.

A fine of 1,200 lei was imposed on a non-professional farm in Eriu Sâncrai.

Two other sanctions, each worth 1,200 lei, were applied to farms in Unimăt and Ghirișa.

At the same time, two warnings were issued in farms in Căpleni and Tiream localities, following the finding of similar deviations regarding the circulation and marketing of animals without the mandatory documents.
Veterinarians and sanitary and veterinary authorities have entered a state of alert in the context of the evolution of diseases considered extremely dangerous for the European livestock sector.

According to official data, outbreaks of avian influenza continue to evolve in several Member States of the European Union, both in commercial farms and in wildlife.

Belgium, Czechia, Germany, Poland, Denmark, France and Norway are among the countries where primary and secondary outbreaks of avian influenza have been reported.

In the same period, African swine fever continues to affect several European countries.

Active outbreaks have been reported in Poland, Romania, Lithuania, Latvia, Germany, Croatia, Spain, Italy, Slovakia, the Republic of Moldova, Estonia, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Hungary.

In Satu Mare County there are already sanitary-veterinary restrictions imposed due to the outbreaks of African swine fever identified in Amati and Turț localities.

In this context, DSVSA Satu Mare announced the start of an inspection program in animal farms in the county.

The actions aim to monitor and identify animals showing clinical signs of diseases transmissible to cattle, sheep, goats and pigs in non-professional households.

The authorized veterinarians will evaluate the animals existing in each farm, and the ------ have the legal obligation to allow their access and to ensure the containment of the animals in order to carry out the controls in appropriate conditions.

Veterinarians also draw attention to the risk posed by sheep and goat pox, after the confirmation of outbreaks in Bistrita-Nasaud and Mureș counties.

DSVSA Satu Mare warns sheep and goat breeders about the major danger that this disease poses to livestock.

According to the authorities, sheep and goat pox is a highly contagious viral disease, caused by a virus from the Poxviridae family, the genus Capripoxvirus.

The disease affects small ruminants and can cause severe economic losses, especially in lambs, where mortality can reach up to 50-70%.

Although the disease is not transmitted to humans, the economic impact on farms and households can be significant, due to restrictions imposed and losses in livestock.

The sanitary-veterinary authorities have also presented the main clinical symptoms that may indicate the occurrence of the disease in farms:

skin lesions around the muzzle, nose, ears, eyelids, abdomen, legs and genitals;
high fever, between 40 and 42 degrees Celsius, in the first days after infection;
decreased appetite and weight loss;
accentuated state of lethargy and apathy;
excessive tearing and nasal discharge, including purulent;
swollen lymph nodes;
lesions in the oral, nasal and ocular mucous membranes, which can cause breathing and feeding difficulties.

The situation of controls and outbreaks monitored by veterinarians in Satu Mare:

Indicator
Official data announced

Number of checks performed
79 controls

Verified areas
Professional and non-professional farms, markets, veterinary practices, veterinary pharmacies

Number of sanctions applied
5 sanctions

Total amount of fines
3,600 lei

Amount of a fine
1,200 lei

Sanctioned localities
Eriu Sâncrai, Unimăt, Ghirișa

Localities with warnings
Căpleni, Tiream

The reason for the sanctions
Sale or alienation of animals without sanitary-veterinary documents

ASF outbreaks in Satu Mare
Amati and Turț

Counties affected by sheep and goat pox
Bistrița-Năsăud și Mureș

Mortality in lamb in severe cases
up to 50-70%""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:31.506831+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.capital.ro/amenzi-pentru-unii-romani-care-stau-la-tara-se-verifica-gospodariile-cu-animale-cine-va-achita-1-200-de-lei.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_amp a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:amp" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "ec0c0d06ea8a83000abd68d6e39d41e3d8f055dff76b0257d4b9ab5a84dd2fbb" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Fines in Satu Mare for the sale of animals" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Fines in Satu Mare for the sale of animals

Fines in Satu Mare for the sale of animals

DSVSA Satu Mare inspectors carried out, between May 15 and 22, 2026, almost 100 controls in animal farms, markets, veterinary sanitary offices and veterinary pharmacies in the county.

The checks concerned the field of animal health and welfare, in the context in which there are sanitary-veterinary restrictions at the county level due to outbreaks of African swine fever, and outbreaks of sheep and goat pox have been reported in other counties in the country.

According to DSVSA Satu Mare, this week 96 controls were carried out in professional and non-professional farms, markets, veterinary sanitary offices and veterinary pharmacies.

Following the checks, the inspectors applied 5 contravention sanctions, of which 3 fines totaling 4,800 lei and 2 warnings.

The sanctions were applied for the sale or alienation of animals without the documents provided by the sanitary-veterinary legislation in force.

Thus, a non-professional farm in Rătești was fined 2,400 lei, and two other non-professional farms, in Dobra and Borlesti localities, were fined 1,200 lei each.

Also, two warnings were applied in farms in Turț and Portița.

DSVSA Satu Mare draws attention to the fact that there are still sanitary-veterinary restrictions in the county caused by outbreaks of African swine fever in Amați, Turț, Resighea, Gereușa and Porumbești.

In this context, the institution continues the program of inspections in the county's animal farms, for the surveillance of cattle, sheep, goats and pigs from the population's households.

------------------------ will assess the animals on each holding.

Animal owners have the obligation to allow the access of concession veterinarians to households and to ensure the containment of the kept animals, so that the assessment can be done correctly.

At European level, according to data provided by DSVSA, avian influenza evolves in 49 primary or secondary outbreaks, both in poultry farms and in the wild, in several states, including Austria, Estonia, Germany, Poland, Denmark, Finland, the Netherlands and Norway.

Also in the European Union, African swine fever evolves in 249 outbreaks, including in Romania, but also in countries such as Poland, Lithuania, Latvia, Germany, Croatia, Spain, Italy, Slovakia, Moldova, Serbia, Ukraine and Hungary.

Another important warning concerns sheep and goat breeders in Satu Mare County.

DSVSA warns about the danger posed by sheep and goat pox, after the appearance of outbreaks in Bistrita-Nasaud and Mureș counties.

Sheep and goat pox is a highly contagious viral disease that affects small ruminants.

The disease is not transmitted to humans, but it can cause major economic losses and high mortality, especially among lambs.

Among the symptoms that should attract the attention of breeders are skin lesions, especially around the muzzle, nose, ears, eyelids, abdomen, legs and genitals, high fever, decreased appetite, weight loss, apathy, nasal and tear secretions, inflammation of the lymph nodes, as well as lesions on the oral, nasal and ocular mucous membranes.

DSVSA Satu Mare recommends animal owners to immediately notify the veterinarian in case of signs of illness and to comply with the measures ordered by the authorities.

For notifications or complaints in the sanitary-veterinary and food safety field, citizens can call the Call Center at 0800 826 787 or DSVSA Satu Mare, at 0261 715 956 and 0760 789 016.""" ;
