tsd:news_padi_web_authorities_assures_cattle_for_eid_al_adha_in_jakarta_to_be_free_from_fmd_and_lsd a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:authorities-assures-cattle-for-eid-al-adha-in-jakarta-to-be-free-from-fmd-and-lsd" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "782e7e45fb678e3bb32c899380db795a61a84996a9662c6e898b1e712daa0f28" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Authorities Assures Cattle for Eid al-Adha in Jakarta to be Free from FMD and LSD" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Authorities Assures Cattle for Eid al-Adha in Jakarta to be Free from FMD and LSD

Authorities Assures Cattle for Eid al-Adha in Jakarta to be Free from FMD and LSD

inp.polri.go.id - Jakarta.

The Jakarta Regional Metropolitan Police, along with the Jakarta Maritime Affairs and Agriculture Agency (KPKP), ensured that sacrificial animals at Perumda Dharma Jaya are free from Foot-and-Mouth Disease (FMD) and Lumpy Skin Disease (LSD).

"We have directly observed the business processes at Dharma Jaya, from production to distribution.

We also ensured and inspected the cleanliness and health of the cattle, including screening for the FM and LSD," explained -----------------------------------------, Director of Special Criminal Investigation of the Jakarta Regional Metropolitan Police, on Thursday (5/21/2026).

The inspection was carried out as part of routine supervision ahead of Eid al-Adha to ensure that the sacrificial animals circulating in the community are healthy and safe.

He explained that to date, his team has not found any indications of FMD or LSD in the livestock at Dharma Jaya.

However, regular monitoring will continue to be conducted to prevent the potential spread of disease.

"Currently, no FMD and LSD has been found in the cattle.

We certainly hope that all parties will continue to monitor and supervise each other," concluded ------.

He added that this monitoring demonstrates the strong collaboration between the police, local government, and the Dharma Jaya Regional Public Company in maintaining the quality of sacrificial animals ahead of Eid al-Adha.

"We hope this preparation will run smoothly until Eid al-Adha is over, so that the public can receive healthy and suitable sacrificial animals," said ------.
(ad/ndt/pr/rs)""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:54:56.214784+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://inp.polri.go.id/artikel/authorities-assures-cattle-for-eid-al-adha-in-jakarta-to-be-free-from-fmd-and-lsd"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_avian_flu_detected_in_cape_fur_seals_for_the_first_time a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:avian-flu-detected-in-cape-fur-seals-for-the-first-time" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "df72b77e9ba5c606b5f67d4bf83cabc50ed35b5696304ba4b08e4d77d020cd5a" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Avian flu detected in Cape Fur Seals for the first time" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Avian flu detected in Cape Fur Seals for the first time

Avian flu detected in Cape Fur Seals for the first time

In early April, a Cape Fur Seal rescued at Mossel Bay in South Africa had to be euthanised because of its poor condition.

The animal hospital caring for it asked that the seal be tested not only for rabies, but also for highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI).

Results received earlier this month confirmed that the seal was infected with bird flu.

This is historic as it’s the first-ever recorded case of bird flu in a Cape Fur Seal.

Cape Fur Seals, which are endemic to Southern Africa, now face threats from two infectious diseases, rabies and avian influenza, in addition to many human-related threats.

Avian influenza is an airborne disease that can spread through infected birds, droppings, contaminated environments and airborne particles.

Seals are most likely infected through direct contact with seabirds or contaminated water.

As seals and seabirds are often found resting or feeding together, and because seals occasionally hunt seabirds, the likelihood of transmission is considered quite high.

It was previously thought that avian flu could not be transmitted to Cape Fur Seals.

NAMIBIAN CONCERN

There is now serious concern that the virus could spread to Namibia’s seal populations, especially as seals and seabirds travel long distances up and down the coastline between Namibia and South Africa.

Many seals showing suspicious, and sometimes aggressive, behaviour have already been observed close to our Namibian colonies.

Because of the remote locations of Cape Fur Seal colonies, only some of these animals have ever been tested.

When examined, it was usually only for rabies.

Namibia has already experienced outbreaks of bird flu.

The first one was detected in penguins in 2019 – more than 500 African Penguins were reported dead on Halifax and surrounding islands.

In 2022, Cape Cormorants were primarily affected.

More than 6 500 birds died in
Namibia alone, threatening populations of an already endangered species.

Most recently, Common Terns were especially affected by bird flu last year.

SYMPTOMS
Signs to look out for in birds include unusual behaviour, seizures or twitching, head nodding, cloudy eyes, or birds that seem unusually tame.

The symptoms in seals are similar.

They include severe lethargy, tremors, seizure-like activity, and breathing difficulties such as coughing or rapid, laboured breathing.

The virus is deadly for both seabirds and seals.

First detected in poultry in 1996, the virus mutated by 2020 and spread easily among wild birds.

By 2022, it was known to spread from mammal to mammal.

In 2023, it caused mass deaths in Southern Elephant Seals in Argentina, killing more than 17 000 pups.

It also caused major losses in South Georgia in 2024, when nearly half of all breeding females were lost.

As of April this year, 36 Northern Elephant Seals, three California sea lions, and one southern sea otter were confirmed to be infected with avian flu in Californiain the United States.

It also the first time the disease has been detected in Northern Elephant Seals.

The situation is concerning and is being closely monitored by authorities in California.

‘DON’T TOUCH’

Although not usually fatal to humans, people can still become infected and experience severe flu-like symptoms.

The public is therefore urged not to touch any animal and to keep a safe distance from any seabird or seal in distress along our coast.

Instead, please immediately notify Ocean Conservation Namibia (OCN) or the state veterinarian if you notice any suspicious behaviour or symptoms.

* ----------------, publicist, educator, seal rescuer and junior researcher at Ocean Conservation Namibia.

He has a master’s in ecology and society from Costa Rica’s University for Peace.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:55:06.930571+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.namibian.com.na/avian-flu-detected-in-cape-fur-seals-for-the-first-time/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_avian_flu_hits_4_us_poultry_farms_polar_bear_norway_island a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:avian-flu-hits-4-us-poultry-farms-polar-bear-norway-island" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "d0f6abe22735cd4729792c3c217bf91826b34cc60b1f8b7702c52a7bac15052d" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Avian flu hits 4 US poultry farms, polar bear on Norway island" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Avian flu hits 4 US poultry farms, polar bear on Norway island

Avian flu hits 4 US poultry farms, polar bear on Norway island

Lisa Zins / Flickr cc

A white-tailed deer at Penn State’s Deer Research Center has tested positive for chronic wasting disease (CWD), leading to a five-year quarantine of the facility and herd, the college announced this week.

The buck, found dead during a routine daily herd check in March, hadn’t displayed signs of CWD before its death, but staff submitted diagnostic samples to the Pennsylvania Animal Diagnostic Laboratory at Penn State, which detected the disease.

The National Veterinary Services Laboratories confirmed the finding on May 5.The campus is located in University Park, Centre County, in the central part of the state.

This isn’t the first CWD detection in the county, where CWD has been detected in wild deer. Continuation of research, education in quarantineThe Penn State Department of Animal Science and the Deer Research Center are working with state officials and have imposed a mandated five-year quarantine of the facility and the remaining herd, the news release said.

So far, no other deer in the herd have shown signs of CWD.“The quarantine plan includes strict containment measures, ongoing monitoring and testing, mandatory reporting, comprehensive documentation of herd inventory, and continued sanitization of the facility,” the release said.

“In addition, staff are evaluating the potential use of genetic testing to understand individual animals’ susceptibility to CWD better.

”The quarantine plan includes strict containment measures, ongoing monitoring and testing, mandatory reporting, comprehensive documentation of herd inventory, and continued sanitization of the facility.

Since it was established in the 1970s, the Deer Research Center has given students hands-on opportunities to work with deer.

The center operates as a closed herd, with no external deer introduced since 1997.

The College of Agricultural Sciences is assessing how research activities and educational programming will proceed during quarantine.

CWD is a fatal neurodegenerative disease of cervids (eg, deer, elk, moose) caused by infectious misfolded proteins called prions, which spread from cervid to cervid and through environmental contamination.

Prions can persist for years in the environment, and animals may be infected for years—silently spreading the disease—before they show symptoms.

No vaccine or treatment is available.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:54:23.835756+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/avian-influenza-bird-flu/avian-flu-hits-4-us-poultry-farms-polar-bear-norway-island"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_az_allategeszsegugyi_felhasznalasbol_kizart_antimikrobialis_hatoanyagok a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:az-allategeszsegugyi-felhasznalasbol-kizart-antimikrobialis-hatoanyagok" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "b40a7c9396e0b9c586eecedaa8f11d70a59727e3f547b4efe82c60b4a3fcb7d3" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Antimicrobial active substances excluded from veterinary use" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Antimicrobial active substances excluded from veterinary use

Antimicrobial active substances excluded from veterinary use
Friday, 22 May, 2026
An important element in the fight against antimicrobial resistance is the promotion of a more prudent use of antimicrobials, which is also a priority in veterinary medicine.

In order to ensure the responsible use of antimicrobials, especially antibiotics, and to reduce the risk of resistance, the provisions of the EU and national legislation governing veterinary medicinal products must be complied with when providing veterinary services.

Based on the "One Health" approach, the relevant EU and national legislation and measures give priority to the protection and preservation of the effectiveness of active substances that are critically important from a human health point of view.

In line with this,
on the definition of antimicrobials or groups of antimicrobials reserved for the treatment of certain human infections in accordance with Regulation (EU) 2019/6 of the European Parliament and of the Council
Regulation (EU) No 2022/1255
contains a list of antimicrobial active substances that must not be used in veterinary medicines, medicated feed or for other veterinary purposes, including off-label use.

As a result of the evaluation carried out by the European Medicines Agency on the basis of the criteria set out in Regulation (EU) 2021/1760

The veterinary use of 18 groups of antibiotics, 18 antiviral agents and one antiprotozoal active ingredient is not allowed from 9 February 2023.

The use of these active substances and groups of active substances in animal health was not typical in Hungary even before this regulation.

At the same time, in order to comply with the law, it must be ensured that the human medicinal products concerned will not be prescribed on veterinary prescription in the future.

The relevant information was sent to the public pharmacies distributing medicinal products containing the given active ingredients through the National Centre for Public Health and Pharmacy in order to ensure that the human medicinal products concerned are not dispensed for veterinary purposes or on veterinary prescription.

At the same time, domestic food chain actors, including veterinary professionals and animal keepers, must pay special attention to the fact that these products are not prescribed and used.

The protection of these active ingredients, the reduction of the risk of resistance, and the preservation of the sensitivity of pathogens serve to protect the health of all of us!

List of active substances to be preserved and prohibited in veterinary medicine:
1.

Antibiotics
Carboxypenicillins
Ureidopenicillins
Ceftobiprol
Ceftarolin
Cephalosporin combinations containing beta-lactamase inhibitors
Siderophoric cephalosporins
Carbapenems
Penems
Monobactams
Phosphonic acid derivatives
Glycopeptides
Lipopeptides
Oxazolidinones
Fidaxomicin
Plasomycin
Glycylcyclines
Private Cycle
Omadacycline
2.

Antiviral drugs
Amantadine
Baloxavir marboxil
Celgosivir
Favipiravir
Galidesivir
Lactimidomycin
Laninamivir
Methisazone/methishasone
Molnupiravir
Nitazoxanide
Oseltamivir
Peramivir
Ribavirin
Rimantadin
Tizoxanide
Triazavir
Umifenovir
Zanamivir
3.Antiprotozoan agents
Nitazoxanide
Legal references:
-
Regulation (EU) No 6/2019
- Regulation (EU) 2022/1255
- 128/2009.

(V. X.) Decree of the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development
News
