/
News
/
Cannabis for medical use, days of study and discussion dedicated to the in-depth study of the Italian management system
Cannabis for medical use, days of study and discussion dedicated to the in-depth study of the Italian management system
SHARE
Share
Release Date
27/05/2026
On 12 and 13 May 2026, representatives of the
Albanian Agency for the Control of Cannabis
they were guests of a study visit organized as part of the European programs TAIEX - Moving Forward Together with EU Expertise, an initiative that supports regulatory adaptation to European Union standards through the transfer of technical skills and good practices.

The program saw the participation of the General Directorate of Medical Devices and Drugs, Central Narcotics Office, as well as the
Italian Medicines Agency
and the
Military Chemical Pharmaceutical Plant of Florence.

Two days of study and discussion dedicated to the in-depth study of the Italian system of management of cannabis for medical use, with particular attention to some aspects that characterize the supply chain:
new European and national scenarios and regulatory updates
Clinical uses
Drug distribution and management
Cultivation authorization, import, export
International reporting
GMP (Good Manufacturing Practices)
GACP (Good Agricultural and Collecting Practices).

The choice of the
Ministry of Health as host authority
confirms the role of the Central Narcotics Office of the Directorate General for Medical Devices and Medicines, together with AIFA and the SCFM, as a model of excellence at international level and represents a first step towards strengthening European synergies on the delicate issue of cannabis.

See also
07/05/2026
-
Drug precursors, EU Regulation 2026/314 extends control to nine new substances
16/04/2026
-
Narcotic substances, the Ministry updates the tables: including the class of nitazones among the banned substances
24/12/2025
-
Fentanyl surveillance: the Ministry of Health intensifies controls on prescriptions and strengthens vigilance
Theme
Narcotic medicines and drug precursors
PRINTABLE VERSION
SHARE
Share
ALL NEWS""" ;
