tsd:news_padi_web_da_qua_thoi_soi_kinh_hien_vi_cung_khong_thay_xuat_khau_chan_nuoi a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:da-qua-thoi-soi-kinh-hien-vi-cung-khong-thay-xuat-khau-chan-nuoi" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "70036740a7c2dd8db8f3d978b8cf6ab231e12727bdd92fc455cd858ede2bac76" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "'The days when livestock exports could not be seen even under a microscope are long gone.'" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# 'The days when livestock exports could not be seen even under a microscope are long gone.'

'The days when livestock exports could not be seen even under a microscope are long gone.'

A veterinary equipment supplier in Ho Chi Minh City sells thousands of products every month, ranging from veterinary devices and diagnostic tools to industrial livestock machinery.

Speaking with a VietNamNet correspondent, a business representative assessed that the domestic market has great potential due to the trend of replacing small-scale domestic livestock farming with large-scale farms in the past.

On an industrial scale, special veterinary equipment will be preferred.

Therefore, the company is looking for foreign partners to expand its supply of veterinary equipment at the ILDEX Vietnam 2026 exhibition.

Former Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Environment Phung Duc Tien, in his speech at the opening ceremony of the exhibition on May 20, stated that the livestock sector is experiencing a strong transition from small-scale production to industrial scale.

Mr. Phung Duc Tien at the opening ceremony of the exhibition.

Photo: Thu Thuy Previously, small-scale livestock farming accounted for 70-76% of the industry.

Currently, with the participation of large enterprises and corporations, this percentage has decreased sharply, falling below 40%.

The livestock sector not only meets the needs of 100 million people and about 20 million tourists every year, but also increases exports.

"Previously, many ministers said that even under a microscope, animal exports could not be seen, but now things have changed," Mr. Tien noted.

In 2025, total meat production is expected to reach 8.68 million tons.

Egg production is expected to reach 21.4 billion and fresh milk production is expected to reach approximately 1.3 million tons.

In the first four months of 2026, livestock exports are estimated to reach $245 million, an increase of 45.5% compared to the same period.

The former deputy minister stated that livestock exports will reach 700-800 million dollars in 2026 and that it is aimed to increase exports excluding animal feed to 1 billion dollars by 2027.

These results were achieved thanks to the long-term restructuring process of the agricultural sector.

Over the years, the livestock sector has established a relatively comprehensive policy framework, from the Livestock Law to guiding decrees and circulars.

"Despite the limited land and large population, Vietnam has often been affected by diseases such as African swine flu, lumpy skin disease, and foot-and-mouth disease, as animal husbandry started with small-scale enterprises... however, we have successfully contained several outbreaks and achieved impressive growth in the livestock sector," emphasized the former Ministry leader.

ILDEX Vietnam, which will take place in Ho Chi Minh City from May 20th to 22nd, is an international exhibition specializing in animal husbandry, dairy production, meat processing, and aquaculture for the Vietnamese and Indochinese markets.

The event brings together more than 230 enterprises and brands from 25 countries and regions such as China, North America, France, the European Union, and South Korea...

Minister Trinh Viet Hung: Don't trade shrimp farming areas for billion-dollar projects.

Vietnam's shrimp industry exported a record $4.6 billion, but at a conference on May 8, industry leaders and businesses unanimously warned of the risk of shrinking growing areas due to planning pressures; Ca Mau, known as the "shrimp capital", was among these warnings.

Source: https://vietnamnet.vn/da-qua-thoi-soi-kinh-hien-vi-cung-khong-thay-xuat-khau-chan-nuoi-2517620.html""" ;
