tsd:news_padi_web_etats_unis_etude_demontre_premiere_fois_transmission_virus_h5n1_chat_lhomme_video a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:etats-unis-etude-demontre-premiere-fois-transmission-virus-h5n1-chat-lhomme-video" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "8adea94814bbefc19760002c7192d04a6add8bce3c81c069ba034edeb22253d7" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "In the United States, a study demonstrates for the first time the transmission of the H5N1 virus from cats to humans (video)" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# In the United States, a study demonstrates for the first time the transmission of the H5N1 virus from cats to humans (video)

In the United

States, a study demonstrates for the first time the transmission of the H5N1 virus from cats to humans (video)

In a study published on May 7, the CDC indicated that there could be "potential contamination with the H5N1 virus" and warned of possible transmission from cats to hum

ans. From November 2024 to January 2025 in the Los Angeles area, there had already been several cases of cats infected with the H5N1 virus, but to date none had been transmitted to humans. 19 cases of contaminated cats In total, 19 cases of cats had presented respiratory distress, liver or neurological problems following contamination by the H5N1 virus. Among these cases, 14 cats di

d or had to be euthanized. The families of the cats that had died o

r

been euthanized were tested, representing 139 people. Of the 25 people who had blood tests, an asymptomatic -------

---- showed evidence of H5N1 infection after being exposed to a cat carrying the infection. Indeed, the ------------ presented a negative test for the virus 7 days after being exposed t

the virus. The causes of the contamination The 19 cats in the investigation had all consumed raw mil

k

, raw meat or raw pet food. The

food had been purchased commercially. This discovery shows for the first time the transmission of this virus from a

omestic animal to a human. The health recommen

dations for cat owners are not to give raw milk, raw meat or any raw food to your pet. 

Pattounes in your mailbox

Let's get started!""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-24"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:51:53.812874+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://wamiz.com/actu/198147/etats-unis-etude-demontre-premiere-fois-transmission-virus-h5n1-chat-lhomme-video"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_eurosurveillance_cross_reactive_human_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:eurosurveillance-cross-reactive-human.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "b194cfb1dc4df95e5dd9ff227b7f3781bb37829efd305f4fb2f897b9229bf5c2" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Eurosurveillance: Cross-reactive human antibody responses to H9N2 influenza virus, New York, United States, 2025" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Eurosurveillance: Cross-reactive human antibody responses to H9N2 influenza virus, New York, United States, 2025

Eurosurveillance: Cross-reactive human antibody responses to H9N2 influenza virus, New York, United States, 2025

Credit NIAID #19,172While LPAI H9N2 remains far from our biggest pandemic concern, the CDC has designated 2 different lineages (A(H9N2) G1 and A(H9N2) Y280) as having at least some pandemic potential (see CDC IRAT SCORE), and several candidate vaccines have been developed.

All of which makes it important to know how much existing immunity their might be in the community should LPAI H9N2 ever embark on a world tour; particularly from regions of the world where the virus has not been circulating.

To that end we have the following Rapid Communication - published yesterday in the journal Eurosurveillance - which looks at a relatively small cohort (n=298) of serum samples collected in NYC between between Feb 2024 and Apr 2025, which they tested for signs of pre-existing immunity against 1 specific strain (A/Changsha/SR353/2025 - Y280 lineage) of LPAI H9N2.

In brief, they found widespread - but weak - cross-reactive haemagglutinin (HA)-binding antibodies among the 298 samples, likely due to previous seasonal flu vaccinations and/or exposures (see comparison chart below).On the other hand, neuraminidase-inhibiting antibodies were more common and stronger.

All this suggests that while protection against H9 infection is likely very limited - and unlikely to create much of a barrier for the spread of the virus - the stronger NA antibodies may help reduce the severity of infection.

At least that's the hope.

Interestingly, there is a small but perceptible dip in both HA and NA inhibition activity in those born in the mid-to-late 1980s and early 1990s, but given the small sample size and weak response, this may not be significant.

Although the news isn't all bad, this study looks at only one small and geographically limited dataset - and one specific strain of LPAI H9N2 - so there is only so much we can infer from their findings.

I've only posted the link and some excerpts below, most will want to follow the link to read the report in its entirety.

Open AccessCross-reactive human antibody responses to H9N2 influenza virus, New York, United States, 2025 Gagandeep Singh1,2 , Disha Bhavsar1,2 , Lucas M Ferreri3 , Jessica R Nardulli1,2 , Charles Gleason1,2 , Neko Lyttle1,2 , Yuexing Chen1,2 , Anice C Lowen3 , Viviana Simon1,2,4,5,6 , Florian Krammer1,2,6,7,8  Avian influenza A(H9N2) viruses have been endemic in poultry for many years across Asia, the Middle East, and Northern and Western Africa and have been detected periodically in the Americas and Europe.

Since their first detection in 1966, H9N2 viruses have evolved into multiple lineages and exhibit a high propensity for reassortment, contributing internal genes to zoonotic viruses such as H5N1, H7N9 and H10N8

[1,2].Human infections with H9N2 viruses have been reported since 1998, with most cases linked to poultry exposure and typically resulting in mild or asymptomatic disease but severe cases and deaths have been observed as well.

Despite these observations, population-level immunity to H9N2 remains poorly defined, particularly in regions without endemic exposure to the virus.

Here, we assessed cross-reactive antibody responses to H9N2 viruses using a panel of recently collected human sera from the general population of a large metropolitan city in North America (New York City)        (SNIP)Our work describes pre-existing immunity at population level to avian influenza A(H9N2) viruses in adults from New York City.

We observed widespread cross-reactive haemagglutinin (HA)-binding antibodies in the sampled group; however, these responses were of lower magnitude than those against seasonal H3.

Consistent with this, HI and neutralising antibody responses to H9N2 were low or undetectable in most individuals, indicating limited functional immunity.

In contrast, a high proportion of individuals exhibited N2-binding and NI antibodies, including cross-reactive responses to H9N2.

Although NA-directed antibodies do not prevent infection, they may reduce viral replication and disease severity, potentially providing the population with some degree of resilience against emerging influenza viruses [6,7].

The comparable magnitude of NI responses to H9N2 and H3N2 suggests that prior exposure to seasonal influenza viruses has generated cross-reactive NA immunity.

This is consistent with historical observations that pre-existing anti-N2 antibodies, induced during circulation of A(H2N2) viruses, may have contributed to reduced disease severity during the emergence of the A(H3N2) pandemic

[17,18].The difference between HA and NA responses is not surprising.

Comparative sequence analysis revealed substantial divergence between the HA proteins of lineage B4.7.2 virus A/Changsha/SR353/2025 (H9N2) and seasonal A/Thailand/8/2022 (H3N2), with only approximately 40% amino acid identity.

In contrast, the N2 neuraminidases of the two viruses showed high conservation, sharing approximately 89% amino-acid identity.

Our study also has several limitations.

Vaccination data were not captured, and we therefore cannot draw any conclusions about the effect of seasonal vaccination on H9N2 immunity.

Furthermore, our analysis was restricted to a small, geographically limited group of individuals.

Finally, different lineages of H9N2 circulate and they are antigenically distinct.

This study only used one of these viruses as reagent and cross-reactive responses to other lineages of H9N2 may differ.

ConclusionIn summary, we found that pre-existing immunity to H9N2 in humans that is dominated by cross-reactive but largely non-neutralising antibodies, with a greater contribution from NA-directed responses.

Given the pandemic potential of H9N2 viruses, these findings have important implications for risk assessment and support the inclusion of NA immunity in vaccine development strategies.

Further studies are needed to confirm whether cross-reactive NI antibodies confer protection against H9N2 infection or modulate disease severity, but our results suggest that the antibodies against H9N2 virus might derive from exposure to conserved epitopes shared between the avian-origin and seasonal strains.

(Continue . . . )""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:43.947301+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://afludiary.blogspot.com/2026/05/eurosurveillance-cross-reactive-human.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_gioi_khoa_hoc_bac_tin_don_ve_chu_ky_dai_dich a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:gioi-khoa-hoc-bac-tin-don-ve-chu-ky-dai-dich" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "490572d761573e770c5716972f1cec41be67f0e1fc28169f6af193e6ef4eee45",
        "f0cb192840dcd12ed305b1bd534cf4218bdf332bd967cc46080872283db12ac6" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Scientists deny rumors of \"pandemic cycles\".",
        "Scientists refute rumors of \"pandemic cycles\"." ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Scientists deny rumors of "pandemic cycles".

Scientists deny rumors of "pandemic cycles".

In Indonesia, a video is circulating on social media claiming that viral outbreaks or pandemics occur in the world every six years, and even suggesting that these outbreaks are "deliberately planned."

According to a VNA correspondent in Jakarta, a video posted on Instagram lists a number of major epidemics such as SARS in 2002, swine flu in 2008, Ebola in 2014, COVID-19 in 2020 and hantavirus in 2026 to demonstrate the aforementioned "cycle".

However, epidemiologists argue that there is no scientific evidence that pandemics always occur at fixed intervals of 6 years.

According to epidemiologist -------------- of Griffith University, scientists estimate that there are approximately 1.6 million types of viruses in nature, and about 800,000 of them have the potential to cause epidemics in humans.

However, mankind has thoroughly studied only a very small part of them.

He stated that the history of modern pandemics shows that the intervals between outbreaks vary greatly: SARS appeared in 2002, H1N1 influenza in 2009, Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) in 2012, and COVID-19 in 2019.

In addition, Ebola, Zika, avian influenza and hantavirus viruses appeared at different times without any specific pattern.

According to this expert, the deliberate choice of certain time frames while ignoring others created the illusion of a "secret pattern."

He stressed that the Ebola virus was actually discovered in the 1970s, while hantavirus is known from the 1950s to the 1970s, not as a recent phenomenon.

Experts also warn that humans have a psychological tendency to look for patterns in random events — a phenomenon known as "apophenia," that is, the tendency to see connections even when there is no clear cause-and-effect relationship.

In addition, scientists advise the public to be cautious about information about the pandemic spread on social media, as conspiracy theories about pandemics often easily cause panic and distort scientific understanding.

According to historical documents published on the scientific platform ScienceDirect, infectious diseases have existed throughout human history, from the Athenian plague of 430 BC to the Plague of Justinian in 541 and many major outbreaks in the modern era.

Experts say that instead of believing in "pandemic cycles", it is much more important to strengthen epidemiological surveillance, virus research and build up global health capacity to prevent the risk of future outbreaks.

Source: https://www.vietnamplus.vn/gioi-khoa-hoc-bac-tin-don-ve-chu-ky-dai-dich-post1112463.vnp""",
        """# Scientists refute rumors of "pandemic cycles".

Scientists refute rumors of "pandemic cycles".

The video circulating on Indonesian social media attracts attention with the claim that the world experiences virus outbreaks or pandemics every six years, and even hinting that these outbreaks are "deliberately organized".

According to a VNA correspondent in Jakarta, a video posted on Instagram lists a number of major epidemics such as SARS in 2002, swine flu in 2008, Ebola in 2014, COVID-19 in 2020, and Hunt virus in 2026 to demonstrate the aforementioned "cycle".

However, epidemiologists say that there is no scientific evidence that pandemics always occur at fixed intervals of 6 years.

According to epidemiologist ------------- of Griffith University, scientists estimate that there are approximately 1.6 million types of viruses in nature, and about 800,000 of them can cause epidemics in humans.

However, humanity has carefully studied only a very small part of them.

He stated that the history of modern pandemics shows that the intervals between outbreaks vary greatly: SARS appeared in 2002, H1N1 influenza in 2009, Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) in 2012 and COVID-19 in 2019.

In addition, Ebola, Zika, bird flu and Hunt virus appeared at different times without any established pattern.

According to this expert, the deliberate choice of certain time frames while ignoring others created the illusion of a "secret pattern".

He emphasized that the Ebola virus was actually discovered in the 1970s, while the Hunt virus has been known since the 1950s and 1970s, and not as a recent phenomenon.

Experts also warn that people have a psychological tendency to look for patterns in random events — a phenomenon known as "apophenia," a tendency to see connections even in the absence of a clear causal relationship.

In addition, scientists advise the public to be cautious of pandemic-related information circulating on social media, as conspiracy theories about pandemics are often easily panicked and distort scientific understanding.

According to historical documents published on the scientific platform ScienceDirect, infectious diseases have appeared throughout human history, from the Athenian plague of 430 BC to the plague of Justinian in 541 and many major outbreaks in the modern era.

Experts say that instead of believing in "pandemic cycles", it is more important to strengthen epidemiological surveillance, virus research and expand global health capacity to prevent the risk of future outbreaks.

Source: https://www.vietnamplus.vn/gioi-khoa-hoc-bac-tin-don-ve-chu-ky-dai-dich-post1112463.vnp""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-25"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:51:17.058738+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime,
        "2026-05-28T19:51:17.817192+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.vietnam.vn/ru/gioi-khoa-hoc-bac-tin-don-ve-chu-ky-dai-dich"^^xsd:anyURI,
        "https://www.vietnam.vn/uk/gioi-khoa-hoc-bac-tin-don-ve-chu-ky-dai-dich"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_giraffe_deaths_caused_by_lumpy_skin_disease a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:giraffe-deaths-caused-by-lumpy-skin-disease" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "2ba517014831a2dd0dde6bea67d8af1d1fdf329749d3dfc1175a56571fe290da" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Giraffe deaths caused by lumpy skin disease" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Giraffe deaths caused by lumpy skin disease

Giraffe deaths caused by lumpy skin disease

Giraffe mortalities may have been caused by lumpy skin disease (LSD), the Namibian Agricultural Union reported in their weekly newsletter dated 8 May 2026.

Last year, from mid-April to the end of May, Namibia experienced an unusual wave of giraffe mortalities across large parts of the country.

Farmers reported finding dead giraffes and observing sick animals displaying abnormal behaviour.

Reports came from areas west and north of Okahandja, extending to Omaruru and Waterberg, as well as farms around Outjo, Okaukuejo and Maroelaboom.

There were also rumours of deaths inside Etosha National Park.

Observed symptoms included drooping ears, excessive drooling, eye discharge and apparent blindness.

Some giraffes developed skin lesions resembling lumpy skin disease (LSD).

Farmers also described lethargic animals standing motionless in the bush and showing little reaction to approaching vehicles or people.

Others appeared disoriented, stumbling over bushes and fences with a staggered, “drunk-like” gait.

Unfortunately, too few samples and questionnaires were submitted to Wildlife Vets Namibia, who sought to determine the cause of mortalities, to determine the exact cause.

Several alternative causes were investigated and ruled out.

These included

Plant poisoning was considered unlikely because the deaths occurred across regions with vastly different vegetation types;
Rabies was excluded after multiple giraffes tested negative;
Lightning strikes were dismissed because many sick animals were seen outside rainy periods and survived for some time before dying, while lightning would have caused instant death.

Insects to blame 
Researchers noted that the outbreak followed an exceptionally good rainy season, which resulted in unusually high insect populations, particularly flies, mosquitoes and midges.

Of the 14 farmer questionnaires received, 71,4% reported significantly higher insect numbers during April and May compared with the previous year.

At the same time, several LSD outbreaks were recorded in cattle in northern Namibia.

Importantly, giraffe mortalities declined sharply with the arrival of the first winter cold spells, which also reduced insect numbers dramatically.

This strongly supports the theory that the disease was spread by insects.

Although isolated cases of LSD in giraffes have previously been reported, Namibia’s 2025 outbreak appears to have been the first largescale event of its kind.

Multiple farmers reported seeing giraffes with the typical skin lesions associated with LSD.

While sheep, goats and most African wild ungulates appear resistant to the disease, impala and springbuck may be susceptible.

What is lumpy skin disease?

Lumpy skin disease is caused by a capripox virus and results in nodular skin lesions on infected animals.

Humans cannot contract the disease.

LSD is widespread throughout Africa and has also spread into parts of Europe, Russia, the Middle East and Asia.

The disease is mainly transmitted mechanically by biting insects such as stable flies, mosquitoes and Culicoides midges.

Certain hard tick species may also spread the virus.

Direct transmission through saliva, contaminated feed or milk may occur, but this route is not yet fully understood.

Warm, wet weather creates ideal breeding conditions for insect vectors, often leading to severe outbreaks.

Long-distance spread is usually associated with the movement of infected animals rather than insects alone.

The virus is highly resilient and may survive for up to a month in dried skin crusts and up to five months in semen.

Signs and impact of LSD
Infected animals usually first develop fever, lethargy and loss of appetite.

Excessive tearing, salivation, nasal discharge and swollen lymph nodes are also common.

This is followed by the appearance of firm skin nodules ranging from 0.5 cm to 5 cm in diameter.

Lesions may occur anywhere on the body but are especially common around the head, neck, udder, scrotum and perineum.

Some animals develop only a few nodules, while others may have hundreds.

As the lesions ulcerate, fluid leaks out and secondary bacterial infections may develop, leading to pus formation and tissue death.

In severe cases, lesions can spread into the respiratory and digestive tracts.

Dairy cattle in peak production are particularly vulnerable and often suffer major drops in milk yield.

Not all infected animals show visible signs.

Up to 50% of cases during an outbreak may remain subclinical.

Mortality rates are usually below 10%, but the economic impact can still be severe due to reduced milk production, weight loss and damage to hides.

Diagnosis and reporting
LSD is a notifiable disease, meaning suspected cases must be reported to a state veterinarian.

Diagnosis is confirmed through skin samples and laboratory testing.

Other diseases can resemble LSD, including pseudo-lumpy skin disease caused by a herpesvirus and Dermatophilus congolensis infections, making laboratory confirmation essential.

PCR testing is commonly used to detect viral genetic material and identify specific virus strains.

Treatment and prevention
There is no specific cure for lumpy skin disease.

Treatment in livestock focuses on managing secondary bacterial infections, reducing fever and supporting recovery through antibiotics, anti-inflammatory medication and vitamins.

Prevention remains the most effective strategy.

Good summer rains combined with high insect numbers should alert farmers to the possibility of an outbreak.

In cattle, vaccination with the attenuated Neethling strain vaccine provides effective protection.

All cattle older than six months should be vaccinated annually, ideally before the rainy season begins.

Fly control is equally important.

Farmers are encouraged to use fly traps and apply insecticides through dipping or spraying.

Severely affected animals may need to be culled to limit spread within herds, although ------- should remember that the virus can survive for weeks in the skin of dead animals.

LSD and wildlife
Very little research exists on the role wildlife plays in the spread of LSD.

Capripoxviruses are among the most serious of all animal poxviruses.

Researchers have found antibodies against capripox viruses in species including wildebeest, springbuck, eland, impala, kudu, waterbuck, reedbuck, giraffe and African buffalo.

The presence of antibodies suggests exposure to the virus, although it does not necessarily mean the animals spread the disease further.

The actual number of infected wild animals may be much higher than reported because skin lesions are often difficult to observe in free-ranging wildlife.

Sick animals may also fall prey to predators before they can be detected.

It is well established that giraffes are susceptible to LSD.

In 1970, a giraffe calf in South Africa was experimentally infected with the virus and died with typical symptoms.

The virus has also been isolated from a giraffe that died in a Vietnamese zoo.

However, infection does not always result in death.

Mortality depends on factors such as infection severity, insect pressure and the animal’s overall condition.

Wildlife veterinarians are urging farmers to report sick or dead giraffes immediately.

Source references
Namibian Agricultural Union (NAU) 8 May 2026 Newsletter
-------- (2026) Lumpy Skin Disease suspected to be behind giraffe deaths Namibian Sun
https://www.namibiansun.com/mw-main/lumpy-skin-disease-suspected-to-be-behind-giraffe-deaths-NMH010388-3015-12287
--------- (2025) Namibia News: Concern about giraffe mortalities
https://proagri.co.za/namibia-news-concern-about-giraffe-mortalities/
Wildlife Vets Namibia
https://wildlifevetsnamibia.com/veterinarywork""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-26"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:50:10.278881+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://proagri.co.za/giraffe-deaths-caused-by-lumpy-skin-disease/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_gumushacikoyde_yagislar_baraj_ve_goletleri_doldurdu a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:gumushacikoyde-yagislar-baraj-ve-goletleri-doldurdu" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "49ccff018952ca4093b35a4a6d560bd725928ad41d18a7c41f0706689c88a136" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Rainfall filled dams and ponds in Gümüşhacıköy" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Rainfall filled dams and ponds in Gümüşhacıköy

Rainfall filled dams and ponds in Gümüşhacıköy

According to the information obtained, the occupancy rate in Çitli Pond in the district reached 100 percent.

Yeni Köy Pond and İmirler Pond were also completely filled and completed their capacity.

The increase in occupancy rates in water resources, which are critical especially for agricultural irrigation, was welcomed by the farmers of the region.

It was learned that due to the rise in the water level in İmirler Pond, an evacuation was made to Ayvalı Pond.

The water level in Balıklı Dam, one of the important water sources of the region, is estimated to be around 80 percent.

Farmers stated that rainfall is of great importance, especially in terms of grain and fruit production, and that the occupancy rates in dams and ponds are promising before the summer season.

Citizens, on the other hand, stated that the filling of water resources this year, after the drought concerns experienced in recent years, will contribute positively to both agricultural production and drinking water needs.

Source: Gümüşhacıköy News""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
