tsd:news_padi_web_iorv_inflammation_and_cardiac_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:iorv-inflammation-and-cardiac.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "e503e7d2292e5182a33c9bb83eaed1a3217a6784625a1ef54496d0044e5548b5" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "IORV: Inflammation and Cardiac Dysfunction in Hospitalized Patients With Influenza: The FluHeart Study" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# IORV: Inflammation and Cardiac Dysfunction in Hospitalized Patients With Influenza: The FluHeart Study

IORV:

Inflammation and Cardiac Dysfunction in Hospitalized Patients With Influenza: The FluHeart Study

#19,174Over the past 15 years we've seen growing evidence that influenza (and other respiratory) infections can raise the risk of heart attacks and strokes, particularly in the acute phase of the illness, with elevated risks that may extend for weeks.

Eurosurveillance: Influenza Vaccination Attenuates Acute Myocardial Infarction and Stroke Risk Following Influenza InfectionJAHA: Viral Infections and Risk of Cardiovascular Disease: Systematic Review and Meta‐AnalysisWhile the exact mechanism isn't fully understood, it appears that severe respiratory infections - which are often accompanied by hypoxemia, increased inflammation, hypotension, and hypercoagulability - can place enormous stresses on the cardiovascular system.

Adding to the growing evidence of an influenza-cardiovascular risk link, we have a prospective Danish study - published this week in Influenza & Other Respiratory Viruses - which found that > half of 241 hospitalized influenza patients showed evidence of cardiac dysfunction.

While this observational study cannot tell us whether influenza inflammation caused these cardiac dysfunctions, it suggests that increased inflammation and degraded cardiac function are often seen in conjunction with hospitalized patients with influenza.

A reminder that respiratory protection (vaccines, masks, good `flu hygiene',etc.) is also very likely heart protection.

Follow the link to read the full report.

MethodsIn

this prospective cohort study conducted in Denmark across three influenza seasons (2021–2022, 2022–2023, and 2023–2024), consecutive hospitalized patients with laboratory-confirmed influenza underwent protocolized echocardiography.

Associations between C-reactive protein (CRP) levels and measures of cardiac function were assessed using multivariable models.

ResultsAmong 241 patients (median age, 73.2 years; IQR, 58.3–82.8; 53% female), 54% had left ventricular (LV) systolic dysfunction (ejection fraction < 50% or global longitudinal strain < 16%), 15% had signs of elevated LV filling pressure (E/e′ ≥ 14), 29% had right ventricular (RV) systolic dysfunction (tricuspid annular plane systolic excursion

[TAPSE] < 1.7 cm or RV free wall strain < 20%), and 31% had pulmonary hypertension (RV systolic pressure

[RVSP] > 40 mmHg).

CRP showed a significant nonlinear association with E/e′, RVSP, and TAPSE.

E/e′ and TAPSE worsened with higher CRP up to 100 mg/L, plateauing thereafter, whereas RVSP worsened at CRP levels > 100 mg/L.ConclusionsCardiac dysfunction was observed in more than half of all examined hospitalized patients with influenza.

Higher levels of inflammation were independently associated with elevated LV filling pressure, pulmonary hypertension, and RV dysfunction, supporting a potential link between influenza infection and cardiac impairment.

(SNIP)DiscussionIn this prospective cohort study of hospitalized patients with laboratory-confirmed influenza infection, we made several key findings.

First, more than half of all patients exhibited LV or RV dysfunction.

Second, higher levels of influenza-related acute systemic inflammation, assessed by CRP, were associated with elevated LV filling pressure (E/e′), pulmonary hypertension (RVSP), and impaired RV systolic function (TAPSE).These associations were independent of age, sex, preexisting cardiac and pulmonary conditions, and time since admission, supporting a potential inflammatory contribution to cardiac dysfunction during influenza infection.

This is the largest echocardiographic study of patients with influenza and the first prospectively conducted study to systematically evaluate cardiac function in patients hospitalized with laboratory-confirmed influenza.

Furthermore, prior echocardiographic studies of influenza have not included speckle tracking technology, which enables more sensitive assessment of myocardial function [17].

The present findings extend previous evidence by suggesting that inflammation during acute influenza infection may contribute to cardiac impairment, beyond what would be expected from preexisting cardiac disease alone [18].Additionally, the observed association between influenza-induced inflammation and cardiac dysfunction may help explain the seasonal increases in hospitalizations for new-onset and preexisting heart failure, as well as cardiovascular mortality, seen during influenza epidemics [4, 19].(SNIP)ConclusionIn this cohort of patients hospitalized with laboratory-confirmed influenza, more than half showed signs of either LV or RV dysfunction.

Increased levels of influenza-induced inflammation were independently associated with elevated LV filling pressure, pulmonary hypertension, and RV dysfunction, indicating a possible direct connection between influenza infection and cardiac dysfunction.

(Continue . . . )

While I'm well past having to worry about dying tragically young - I'd still like to postpone the inevitable - so I get the flu shot every year, I've stayed current with my COVID vaccines, and have just added the Prevnar 20 pneumonia vaccine to my previous pneumovax protection.

Everyone has to make their own risk-reward calculation, of course.

And none of these steps are guaranteed to be 100% effective.

But at my age, I'll take whatever advantage I can get.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:21.997906+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://afludiary.blogspot.com/2026/05/iorv-inflammation-and-cardiac.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_kazahstan_poluchil_status_edinstvennoy_strani_v_tsa_svobodnoy_ot_yashura a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:kazahstan-poluchil-status-edinstvennoy-strani-v-tsa-svobodnoy-ot-yashura" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "c98572c26ab6b2ed7cf0f9e72d798c00f15a6ee51883133afb526037f7ce236a" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Kazakhstan received the status of the only country in Central Asia free of foot-and-mouth disease" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Kazakhstan received the status of the only country in Central Asia free of foot-and-mouth disease

Kazakhstan received the status of the only country in Central Asia free of foot-and-mouth disease

This makes it possible to significantly expand the export opportunities of domestic products and open new foreign markets.

What happened
Kazakhstan has become the only state in Central and East Asia with the status of a country free of foot-and-mouth disease, Qumash.kz reports.

This decision was made by the World Organization for Animal Health.

This event was preceded by two years of hard work.

"In 2025, large-scale work was carried out to restore and internationally recognize the welfare statuses for a number of animal diseases, including foot-and-mouth disease in the southeastern regions of the country, highly pathogenic avian influenza, African swine fever, classical swine fever and African horse fever," the Ministry of Agriculture said in a statement.

Why is it necessary?

The status of a country free of foot-and-mouth disease allows Kazakhstan to significantly expand the export opportunities of domestic products and open new foreign markets.

China has already opened a market for Kazakh producers for the supply of slaughter cattle, cattle hides and poultry meat.

Azerbaijan has allowed the import of camels, meat of cattle and small ruminants, poultry, dairy products, honey and fish.

Mongolia is ready to buy live small cattle from Kazakhstan.

Iraq has approved the supply of slaughter cattle and small cattle.

Georgia has allowed the import of slaughter cattle, as well as slaughter and consumer cattle.

Iran has opened the market for the skins and wool of ungulates, and the countries of the European Union - for Kazakh honey.

Context
Foot-and-mouth disease is an acute and highly contagious viral disease that affects cloven-hoofed animals (cows, pigs, sheep, goats), and can also be transmitted to humans.

Subscribe to the official Telegram channel Qumash.kz""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:16.322121+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://qumash.kz/news/kazahstan-poluchil-status-edinstvennoy-strani-v-tsa-svobodnoy-ot-yashura/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_kazahstan_poluchil_status_strany_svobodnoj_ot_yashhura a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:kazahstan-poluchil-status-strany-svobodnoj-ot-yashhura" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "aca81886040bfd67b93400a1118ccd8a7544197c4e0870ffe8fd32408666f20b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Kazakhstan received the status of a country free of foot-and-mouth disease" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Kazakhstan received the status of a country free of foot-and-mouth disease

Kazakhstan received the status of a country free of foot-and-mouth disease

Photo source: Ministry of Agriculture of the Republic of Kazakhstan 
At the 93rd General Session of the World Organization for Animal Health (WOAH) in Paris, delegates from 183 member countries decided to assign Kazakhstan the status of a safe zone for FMD with vaccination.

The official certificate was presented to the Kazakh delegation today, May 22.

This was reported by the press service of the Ministry of Agriculture.

Thus, the entire territory of Kazakhstan is now covered by internationally recognized FMD well-being zones that meet WOAH standards.

Among the countries of East and Central Asia, Kazakhstan is the only one with such a status, the Ministry of Agriculture noted.

The government has been working to obtain this status since 2024.

As part of the preparation and assessment of the country's veterinary system, a set of veterinary preventive, monitoring, organizational and control measures was implemented aimed at ensuring epizootic well-being, increasing the efficiency of veterinary supervision and improving the biosafety system.

"Kazakhstan is consistently strengthening the system of internationally recognized epizootic well-being and confirms the high level of national veterinary safety.

Today, the entire territory of the country is covered by internationally recognized FMD-free zones with vaccination, which is an important result of the state's systematic work.

Along with this, Kazakhstan annually confirms the official status of well-being for African Horse Fever and Classical Swine Fever, and also supports self-declarations on highly pathogenic avian influenza and African swine fever in accordance with the requirements of WOAH," said ----------------------------------------.

According to him, the assignment of this status will strengthen the international position of Kazakhstan, increase confidence from foreign trade partners, as well as expand the export potential of domestic livestock products.

――― ---------------, 22.05.2026""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:09.684919+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://paddock.pro/2026/05/22/kazahstan-poluchil-status-strany-svobodnoj-ot-yashhura/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_la_grippe_aviaire_detectee_chez_un_ours_polaire_dans_larctique a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:la-grippe-aviaire-detectee-chez-un-ours-polaire-dans-larctique" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "385f6e3933a932dea70f6757105801c5328b8382b857dc29143ec78879b0496b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear

Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear

Avian influenza detected in polar bears. This respiratory path

logy of avian origin crossed biological barriers for the first time in European Arctic ecosystems when its fatal presence was confirmed in a large terrestrial predator.

Necropsies performed on brain tissue support the theory th

at the viral infection was the direct trigger for his death. This scenario repeats contagion patterns already seen in Alaskan wildlife, sounding the al

rm about the vulnerability of populations confined to the pole.
Norwegian authorities announced on Tuesday that bird flu had been detected for the first time

in Europe in a polar bear in the Arctic region of Svalbard. 
Avian flu detected in a polar bear caused its death
The H5N5 variant of the virus was detected in samples taken from a male bear about a year old and a walrus found dead in mid-May in the frozen archipelago, about 1,000 km from the North Pole, according to the Norwegian Veterinary Institute. 

"The findings are part of a trend in which more and more highly pathogenic avian influenza viruses are being detected in mammals in Europe," ------------------, coordinator of avian influenza at the Veterinary Institute, said in a statement.
Avian influenza has been detected in polar bears and Norwegian authorities say that: "At the same time, in recent years, the virus has spread to new regions, including the Arctic, where it can have consequences for vulnerable populations and ecosystems," he added.
Avian influenza detected in polar bears and studying the consequences of this fact
The governor of Svalbard said separately that the presence of the virus in the brain samples of the two animals "is consistent with the hypothesis that it was most likely the cause" of their deaths.

In 2023, a dead walrus from bird flu had already been found in Svalbard, and in the same year, the virus was also detected in a dead polar bear in Alaska.
Between January 2025 and March 2026, 140 million animals died or were slaughtered due to bird fl

u in nearly 70 countries, according to the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE).
This is much lower than the peak recorded in 2021-2022, but the virus has since spread widely among non-avian species, increasing the risk of transmission to humans.
On a global scale, animal mortality due to this health crisis has been in the tens of millions in recent mon

ths. Although the total number of poultry casualties has decreased compared to previous crises, the scientific community is very concerned about the increasing adaptability of the pathogen in warm-blooded or

ganisms.
This constant mutation of avian influenza and the shift to new hosts not only threatens the ec

logical stability of remote nature reserves. The fact that they detect avian influenza in polar bears increases the danger of possible community transmission in humans.
The entry Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bears was first

published on ECOticias.com.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:33.509626+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.especes-menacees.fr/la-grippe-aviaire-detectee-chez-un-ours-polaire-dans-larctique/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_la_vaccinazione_per_laviaria a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:la-vaccinazione-per-laviaria" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "e6b2dc44b02eb90b47e28548d6b4bf6840ef9e01357b51d884fb80416520034b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Vaccination for avian flu" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Vaccination for avian flu

Vaccination for avian flu

Since May 2026, the Ministry of Health has launched a pilot vaccination project against highly pathogenic avian influenza, in collaboration with the Veneto and Lombardy regions, on a limited number of farms in the provinces of Verona and Mantua, a project concerning turkeys for meat and laying hens.

Calls to boycott companies participating in this pilot project have begun to appear on social media, indicating AIA as the only brand currently to be boycotted.

But the Ministry's managerial device identifies exactly 5 farms involved: 3 of broiler turkeys in the province of Verona and 2 of laying hens in the province of Mantua.

AIA does not know, nor does it emerge from any official source, that it is the only company to take part.

As reported by Telenuovo's Veronese TG, from 2020 to the beginning of 2026 there were 477 outbreaks of highly pathogenic avian influenza in Italian farms.

Numbers that have pushed towards overcoming emergency management based on culling, focusing on prevention and biosecurity, as also highlighted by the Istituto Zooprofilattico Sperimentale delle Venezie.

Those who push to boycott a single operator by explicitly naming him, while remaining silent about all the other participants in the same project, are at least exposing themselves to a reflection on the issue of unfair competition.

But it is not unfair competition that we want to talk about today, but about vaccines and avian flu.

The very first thing to say is that the messages calling for a boycott of AIA are pure misinformation, because we are talking about an mRNA vaccine, but the management device of the Ministry of Health that gives authorization to this vaccination test phase clearly states which vaccine can be used in the five farms, and it is not mRNA, but:
Beef turkeys
a) First vaccination: recombinant vaccine authorised for turkey with turkey herpesvirus (HVT) vector expressing the hemagglutinin H5 gene, administered in a hatchery on the first day of life.

(b) Second vaccination (booster): Inactivated vaccine authorised for turkey with subunits for H5, containing only the key protein of the virus (haemagglutinin, HA) and not the whole virus, administered at 30 to 36 days of age.

Pullets
a) First vaccination: recombinant vaccine authorised for chicken with HVT vector expressing hemagglutinin H5, administered in a hatchery on the first day of life.

(b) Second vaccination (booster): Inactivated H5 subunit vaccine authorised for chicken, containing only the key protein of the virus (haemagglutinin, HA) and not the whole virus, administered between 10 and 12 weeks of age.

The recombinant vaccine
It is a technology in use in veterinary medicine since the nineties, so if you worry today it is definitely late.

But to fully clarify let's try to understand what we are talking about.

This type of vaccine works like this: you take a virus that is already known and harmless to humans – in this case it is the turkey herpesvirus, which has been used for decades as a vaccine against Marek's disease – and insert the gene that codes for hemagglutinin H5, the surface protein of the avian flu virus.

The vector enters the animal's cells and produces that protein, training the immune system to recognize it.

No live influenza viruses are inoculated, no mRNA, and no modification to the animal's DNA occurs.

All very simple, and the booster of the second vaccination is even simpler since it is an inactivated vaccine that contains only the purified protein, without any genetic material.

Those who talk about "chicken mRNA" vaccination either don't know what they're talking about or are riding on misinformation to stimulate the indignation of an easily suggestible public.

As we have been saying for some time, fear is very useful when trying to influence public opinion.

Wrapping up
If I were in the Ministry of Health, I would immediately trigger complaints for procured alarm, as well as for possible damage to the companies mentioned.

But -'m just a fact checker.

----------- at Butac Punto IT
If you liked the article, support us on Patreon or PayPal!

Even the cost of a coffee can be enough!

Another way to support us is to buy one of the recommended books on our Amazon page, you can find it here.

BUTAC is also waiting for you on Telegram with the channel with all the updates.

Header image by Collab Media on Unsplash""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:46.028350+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.butac.it/la-vaccinazione-per-laviaria/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_libera_al_nuovo_piano_nazionale_della_prevenzione_2026_2031_0 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
