    ts:sourceContentHash "b39321766f752fc12f0e1360039d8822cc532c8e5b3e1284e2fdb629d2a65152" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Green light for the new National Prevention Plan 2026-2031" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Green light for the new National Prevention Plan 2026-2031

Green light for the new National Prevention Plan 2026-2031

Home
/
Communication and data
/
Institutional communication
/
News
/
Green light for the new National Prevention Plan 2026-2031
Green light for the new National Prevention Plan 2026-2031
SHARE
Share
Date of update
21/05/2026
With
State-Regions Agreement of 21 May 2026
the new National Prevention Plan (PNP) 2026-2031 has been adopted.

"The Plan represents a fundamental strategic tool for the planning, throughout the national territory, of health promotion and prevention interventions for the coming years" - underlines the Minister of Health, Orazio Schillaci.

All Regions and Autonomous Provinces will now have to draw up and adopt their own Regional Prevention Plans (PRP), the assessment of which is part of the requirements of the Essential Levels of Assistance (LEA) verification system.

Compared to previous Plans, the PNP 2026-2031 provides for a strengthening of the resources dedicated to prevention, with an additional 50 million euros allocated for 2026 to support territorial preventive activities and the obligations provided for by the State-Regions Agreement.

The PNP 2026-2031, in continuity with the previous one, confirms the approach
One Health
as a guiding principle of prevention policies, promoting an integrated vision of human, environmental and animal health.

The Plan also focuses on intersectorality and the strengthening of interventions in the different contexts of life and work, throughout the life course, to make prevention more effective and equitable throughout the country.

Compared to the previous one, the new Plan aims to strengthen the uniformity of prevention interventions throughout the country.

The Regions will pursue, in fact, predefined and binding objectives for 14 thematic areas, starting with cancer screening with particular reference to the gradual expansion of colorectal screening to the 70-74 age group and mammography screening between 45-49 and 70-74 years.

Among the main innovations of the new Plan is the strengthening of the coordination of prevention policies, with an organizational model structured at national, regional and local level, designed to make interventions more effective and integrated.

In this perspective, the establishment of a Plan Coordination Group, composed of central and regional health institutions engaged in prevention and health promotion, and an inter-institutional Table, composed of Ministries and Bodies from various sectors, involved in the objectives of the National Plan and Regional Plans, according to the model of "Health in all policies", is envisaged.

There are seven priority areas of intervention for public health identified in the PNP 2026-2031:
Chronic non-communicable diseases
Dependencies and related issues
Road and domestic accidents
Health, safety and well-being of workers
Environment, climate and health
Priority infectious diseases
Food safety and veterinary public health
It is also planned to start a collaboration with Agenas for the definition of reference standards for prevention departments to improve efficiency also with an adequate allocation of personnel, as well as a project, as part of the CCM Program, for the evaluation of the economic repercussions of health prevention and health promotion interventions.

See also
