tsd:news_padi_web_niederlande_vogelgrippe_in_einer_milchkuhherde_war_einzelfall_20025624_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:niederlande-vogelgrippe-in-einer-milchkuhherde-war-einzelfall-20025624.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "dc2edc2fb71426ec0945614f15af6f8c4f1b3c09a08939f6d83d37ee2070c095" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Netherlands: Bird flu in a dairy cow herd was an isolated case" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Netherlands: Bird flu in a dairy cow herd was an isolated case

Netherlands: Bird flu in a dairy cow herd was an isolated case

After the outbreak of bird flu in a dairy cow herd in Friesland, Dutch authorities have now finally determined that this was an isolated case and that the virus has not spread further.

Neither -------, ------------- nor neighboring farms had been infected.

This is reported by the Dutch trade magazine Melkvee, among others.

At the end of 2025, the country's food safety authority (NVWA) had tested positive for the bird flu virus in two farm cats that fell ill and later died.

The cows showed no symptoms of illness.

However, the authorities were able to detect antibodies against the virus in milk samples.

Thus, it was clear that some animals must have been infected in the past.

Comprehensive screening was able to detect the antibodies in 47% of the cows and 63% of the young animals.

The dairy cow farmer, his family and the ------------ were also tested, but were negative.

It remained unclear how the infection could have occurred.

An interdisciplinary team of experts for zoonoses, the Response Team Zoönose (RT-Z), has investigated this question.

They have analysed past data as well as tank milk samples or blood samples, including from neighbouring farms.

The affected farm was monitored over a longer period of time.

Neither in the tank milk nor in blood samples could the experts detect further infections with bird flu.

Therefore, the experts of the RT-Z now come to the conclusion that the case in Friesland seems to be an isolated case and that infections of cattle with bird flu occur only very rarely.

The Frisian dairy farm is the first and so far only farm in Europe where antibodies against bird flu have been detected.

The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had stressed at the end of 2025 that an introduction of the US virus strain into European dairy cow herds is very unlikely - but called for vigilance among cattle farmers and veterinarians.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
