tsd:news_padi_web_reminder_key_marketing_and_welfare_requirements_eggs_and_laying_hens a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:reminder-key-marketing-and-welfare-requirements-eggs-and-laying-hens" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "4a72ac63bafeb96f1a630f01cab4c823e6ac6306b11506dc5fb67eb4463e4ad6" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Reminder of Key Marketing and Welfare Requirements for Eggs and Laying Hens" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Reminder of Key Marketing and Welfare Requirements for Eggs and Laying Hens

Reminder of Key Marketing and Welfare Requirements for Eggs and Laying Hens

Date published: 
26 May 2026

 Following the recent lifting of avian influenza restrictions, DAERA has today provided guidance to the industry of its statutory obligations, particularly in relation to free range egg production.

EU Egg Marketing Regulations remain directly applicable under the Windsor Framework, and the Welfare of Farmed Animals Regulations continue to apply.

In particular, following the removal of the Veterinary Housing Order, producers must carefully consider the requirement for birds to have direct access to the range as they readjust to outdoor conditions.

“Direct” access to range requires that from the popholes hens can see and easily access an open-air run that is mainly covered with vegetation and provides appropriate overhead cover.

Care should be taken to avoid structures or surfaces that may hinder birds’ ability or willingness to access any part of the range.

Evidence of compliance includes birds exhibiting normal behaviour and actively accessing and dispersing throughout the range area.

DAERA recognises that, particularly where units have been converted to free range production, access to the required range area may be restricted by roads, lanes or waterways.

Where roads or lanes must be crossed, the construction of tunnels, underpasses or overpasses for the hens will be needed.

These should be carefully designed, taking account of height, width, drainage and light penetration, to encourage (rather than impede) the hens’ natural ranging behaviour.

Producers intending to commence table egg production or make changes to an existing egg laying establishment must apply to DAERA’s Egg Marketing Inspectorate at least one month in advance of placing hens or implementing any changes.

This ensures sufficient time for necessary process.

Further information.

Notes to editors:
Follow DAERA on X formerly called Twitter and Facebook.

All media queries should be directed to the DAERA Press Office: pressoffice.group@daera-ni.gov.uk or telephone: 028 9016 3460.The Executive Information Service operates an out of hours’ service for media enquiries only between 1800hrs and 0800hrs Monday to Friday and at weekends and public holidays.

The duty press officer can be contacted on 028 9037 8110.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-26"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:50:06.509786+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/news/reminder-key-marketing-and-welfare-requirements-eggs-and-laying-hens"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_seuchen_ausbruch_naechste_deutsche_region_richtet_sperrzone_ein_299122 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:seuchen-ausbruch-naechste-deutsche-region-richtet-sperrzone-ein-299122" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "1938bcbe71a4568daec353f670e05c04a8c521f8c67f8dee4c3f60e08aea01b1" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Epidemic outbreak: Next German region establishes exclusion zone" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Epidemic outbreak: Next German region establishes exclusion zone

Epidemic outbreak:

Next German region establishes exclusion zone

Symbolic image © imago/Design Pics

The authorities are cracking down, because a dangerous epidemic continues to advance with great strides.

One consequence of this is the first exclusion zones and other measures to contain the spread.

The citizens of the neighboring region are worried because the epidemic is spreading threateningly.

The Ministry of Agriculture has now intervened and proposed an expansion of existing exclusion zones.

This is to prevent worse.

Ministry of Agriculture drastically expands the exclusion zones
Since yesterday, every interested citizen can view the valid general decree on the website of the Altenkirchen district.

The positive thing in advance: So far, African swine fever has not yet arrived in the Altenkirchen district, but an outbreak is getting closer and closer.

According to official information, there are only 12 kilometers left to the next confirmed case.

Thus, not only the worries are increasing, but above all the preventive precautions to finally contain the dangerous epidemic.

In essence, it is about an expansion of the existing exclusion zone - so a new one will not be added.

Epidemic outbreak: Precautionary measures must be observed in forest areas
The seven-kilometre exclusion zone I includes the towns of Grünebach, Daaden and Herdorf.

To secure the exclusion zone, the responsible ministry is installing fences.

The corresponding planning has taken place on site.

---------------------- ---------------- also addresses reassuring words to the population.

Citizens do not have to worry at all for the time being.

According to his statement, panic is not appropriate.

The expansion of the current barrier fences only serves protection and is intended as a preventive measure to prevent further spread of swine fever.

In addition, the population is unlikely to be severely restricted in this context.

Of the areas that belong to this exclusion zone, pig farmers and hunters are particularly affected.

In the forest regions, it is important to strictly adhere to the precautionary measures.

The virus is highly contagious, which is why dogs are only allowed to run on a leash.

The danger is too high that a dog could simply startle a wild boar.

If he were to touch an infected carcass, the dog could carry the virus further.

In addition, -------- should report dead wild boars to the responsible police station, but never touch the animals.

In the area of the exclusion zones and risk areas, all citizens should only stay on paved and designated paths.

(Sources: Editors' own research)""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:53.767037+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.karlsruhe-insider.de/news/seuchen-ausbruch-naechste-deutsche-region-richtet-sperrzone-ein-299122"^^xsd:anyURI .

