National strategy on health and safety at work, approved by the State-Regions Conference
National strategy on health and safety at work, approved by the State-Regions Conference
SHARE
Share
Date of update
21/05/2026
On 21 May 2026, the State-Regions Conference approved, by formal agreement, the National Strategy for Health and Safety in the Workplace 2026-2030.

This is the first organic and shared plan at national level dedicated to the prevention of accidents and the protection of workers' health.

"Italy is equipping itself for the first time with a shared tool on the subject," said Health Minister Orazio Schillaci.

"The prevention of accidents and the protection of health in the workplace finally become the subject of a structural and binding plan at national level that strengthens the synergy between the State, the Regions and the bodies in charge.

As of today, we have an organic strategy, capable of directing prevention, surveillance and training actions in a coordinated manner throughout the country for the next five years.

We have laid the foundations for a profound change in the way we deal with the issue by involving all the actors with clear tasks.

This means giving concrete attention to workers, their well-being, their safety".

The document was drawn up by the Committee for the guidance and coordination of supervision in the field of health and safety at work, chaired by the Minister of Health and composed of Ministries, Regions, INAIL and the National Labour Inspectorate, with the involvement of the social partners during the consultation phase.

The Strategy was created with the aim of addressing the transformations of the labor market and significantly reducing accidents and deaths at work, adopting for the first time in Italy the "Vision Zero" principle, according to which every accident can be preventable.

The plan, which is already operational, is developed around five main points:

Facing changes in work - Providing answers to the challenges of digitization, artificial intelligence, ecological transition and new forms of contract.

Strengthen the resilience of the institutional system - Strengthen coordination between supervisory bodies (ASL, INL) for more targeted and effective controls.

Strengthen protections - Extend protection to all workers, with particular attention to the sectors at greatest risk and the most fragmented contexts.

Supporting Micro, Small and Medium-sized Enterprises - Accompanying MSMEs in the adoption of good practices, simplifying compliance and raising training standards.

Spreading the culture of prevention - Promoting risk awareness from the school desks, building the generation of workers and employers of tomorrow.

The Strategy will not be a static document.

The Committee for the Guidance and Coordination of Supervision in the Field of Health and Safety at Work will maintain its control room with an annual review system, ensuring the ability to adapt to rapid developments in the production and technological context.

The objectives envisaged will be accompanied by measurable and verifiable indicators, to ensure transparency and effectiveness of the actions undertaken.

To learn more
