tsd:news_padi_web_vogelgrippe_breitet_sich_bei_saeugetieren_in_europa_aus_120198365 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:vogelgrippe-breitet-sich-bei-saeugetieren-in-europa-aus-120198365" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "1d5ab28067c402636339bc69db0df8349fc3143de04f9b5881c0786300ad2d1c" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Bird flu reaches the Arctic - even polar bears are victims" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Bird flu reaches the Arctic - even polar bears are victims

Bird flu reaches the Arctic - even polar bears are victims

Many different mammal species are affected by the dreaded bird flu virus in Europe.

In 2023, the bird flu virus was detected for the first time in a polar bear – a young male in Alaska.

According to the Norwegian Veterinary Institute, the animal now found in Spitsbergen was infected with the H5N5 subtype.

This type has previously been detected in Svalbard in birds, but also in a walrus and arctic foxes."

The findings are part of a development in which the bird flu virus is increasingly detected in mammals in Europe."

-------------------------------- recent years, the virus has also spread to new areas, such as the Arctic.

There it could have an impact on endangered animal populations and the entire ecosystem."

Set "Today" as your preferred source on GoogleAddThe bird flu virus has already been detected in several mammal species in Europe.

In addition to cows and cats, various predators were also affected, from mink, lynx and bear to seals and grey seals.

Infection of humans with the virus is possible in principle, but it is rare.

{----- && {-----} } red, {----- && {-----} } 21.05.2026, 09:23""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-21"^^xsd:date ;
