tsd:news_padi_web_vogelgrippe_erster_eisbaer_in_europa_infiziert_120198731 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:vogelgrippe-erster-eisbaer-in-europa-infiziert-120198731" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "6abcc883fb386e483aa7b2b4e20c59210694bd1e25d80a8466dc12b735222ab8" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Bird flu: First polar bear infected in Europe" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Bird flu: First polar bear infected in Europe

Bird flu: First polar bear infected in Europe

In Norway, a polar bear has tested positive for the bird flu virus for the first time in Europe.

The dead one-year-old male animal was discovered on the Svalbard archipelago.

The virus was also detected in an adult dead walrus."

The findings are part of a development in which the bird flu virus is increasingly detected in mammals in Europe," explained ------------------ from the Norwegian Veterinary Institute.

Set "Today" on Google as your preferred sourceAddAs spiegel.de reports, the polar bear was infected with the H5N5 subtype of the virus.

This type had previously been discovered in Svalbard in birds, a walrus and arctic foxes.

Virus spreads in the ArcticIn 2023, the bird flu virus was detected in a polar bear for the first time worldwide - in a young male in Alaska.

Since then, the virus has spread to new areas, including the Arctic.

The bird flu virus has already been found in many mammal species in Europe.

In addition to cows and cats, various species – from mink and lynx to seals and grey seals – were affected.

Avian influenza was also detected in a sheep in Great Britain.

Infection of humans is possible in principle, but rare.

{----- && {title} } tec, {----- && {-----} } 23.05.2026, 18:52""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
