tsd:news_padi_web_vogelgrippe_erstmal_bei_eisbaer_in_europa_nachgewiesen a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:vogelgrippe-erstmal-bei-eisbaer-in-europa-nachgewiesen" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "1412ad21398aa913fdda1323e399039502bc4836bb072e2978abf634747441ab" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Bird flu detected in polar bear in Europe for the first time" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Bird flu detected in polar bear in Europe for the first time

Bird flu detected in polar bear in Europe for the first timeBird flu continues to make headlines.

Now there has been a particularly worrying case in Norway: For the first time in a polar bear in Europe, the animal disease has broken out.

In Norway, a polar bear has fallen ill with bird flu.

© Unsplash/Hans-Jürgen Mager Norway has reported the first case of bird flu in a polar bear in Europe.

The affected animal was an approximately one-year-old male from the Spitsbergen archipelago.

After his death, the animal was examined, and the virus was detected.

This is reported by the Norwegian Veterinary Institute.

In addition, the virus was detected in an adult, also dead walrus.

Bird flu confirmed in dead polar bear in NorwayRagnhild Tønnessen of the Veterinary Institute commented on the news in a statement.

"The findings are part of a development in which the bird flu virus is increasingly detected in mammals in Europe."

The virus has also penetrated new regions in recent years.

Among other things, the Arctic.

According to ---------, it could have an impact on endangered animal species and the sensitive ecosystem.

In addition to birds, arctic fox and walrus also affectedPreviously, there was already a single case in which the bird flu virus was detected in a polar bear.

This was also a young male found in Alaska in 2023.

The polar bear in Spitsbergen was demonstrably ill with the H5N5 variant.

In addition to the walrus and individual birds, this subtype has also affected an arctic fox in Norway so far.

Mammals repeatedly infected with bird fluMammals are also infected with the bird flu virus again and again, including domestic cats.

For humans, infection is just as possible, but in fact rare.

So far, illnesses have only occurred in the case of increased contact with birds, for example through work in poultry farms.

For all other people, the risk of infection is low.

Growing up in the countryside in Schleswig-Holstein, --- developed a close connection to nature at an early age.

During her German studies, --- also discovered her passion for editorial work.

As a ----- author, --- deals with everything that moves the hunting world around forests and game.""" ;
