    ts:sourceContentHash "7b91b163830873091553359a4bebcfdc8621bc2f169d45d0fa0c50f823c2efe8" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "XXV Day of Relief, I take care" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# XXV Day of Relief, I take care

XXV Day of Relief, I take care

Home
/
Communication and data
/
Institutional communication
/
News
/
XXV Day of Relief, I take care
XXV Day of Relief, I take care
SHARE
Share
Release Date
22/05/2026
"For twenty-five years, this Day has seen us all committed to giving substance to Gigi Ghirotti's message, which drew attention to the need to give an increasingly human face to the National Health Service".

This was said by the Minister of Health, Orazio Schillaci, in his message of greeting to the Gigi Ghirotti National Foundation onlus on the occasion of the XXV Day of Relief which is celebrated on May 31, 2026.

"Since the establishment of Law 38 of 2010 - added the Minister - many steps forward have been taken to strengthen the networks of palliative care and pain therapy, increase the offer of care and to ensure the homogeneous application, throughout the national territory, of the legislation to reduce the persistent territorial disparities.

The challenge today is to increasingly guarantee, all together, access to palliative care to people who need it, overcoming the territorial inequalities that still persist".

The
National Day of Relief
has been
established on 24 May 2001, by directive of the President of the Council of Ministers, on the proposal of the Minister of Health, to promote solidarity and the culture of relief from physical and moral suffering.

"I take care" is the message of the XXV Day of Relief, which will see information and awareness initiatives promoted by the Gigi Ghirotti National Foundation and the Conference of Regions and Autonomous Provinces throughout the country.

Caring, as the Gigi Ghirotti Foundation recalls, is "a basic attitude and act for hospital and general practitioners, nurses, psychologists, technicians, volunteers, as well as for anyone who takes care of those who suffer, aiming for relief in all its dimensions: physical, psychological, spiritual and social and not only for healing, even more so when the latter is no longer achievable,  as happens in terminal diseases".

See on the website of the Gigi Ghirotti National Foundation:
XXV Day of Relief
